{"type":"text","timestamp":1782487017120,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"id":"prt_f04810a8e00162AfGzswCdQvcS","messageID":"msg_f04808072001FIfGI2zYQRHcqY","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","type":"text","text":"Phase init will create a fresh lineage packet because the bound directory has no canonical config/state/strategy yet. I’m gathering evidence for the single research iteration before writing the state packet.","time":{"start":1782486993550,"end":1782487017113},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0f51f328f999505f016a3e97d183e8819183295ab3086ccfcf","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487017222,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_9FVGaYb4ZzB632oTytKj9XnY","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"Brand|Product|Codex|Gemini|bolder|quieter|distill|anti-slop|register","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/impeccable.md","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/overdrive.md:\n  Line 77: - **`@property`** (all browsers): register custom CSS properties with types, enabling animation of gradients, colors, and complex values that CSS can't normally interpolate.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 22: 5. **Brand assets that already exist** - logo, color, type, photography. For redesigns, these are starting material, not optional input (see Section 11).\n\n  Line 94: | GitHub-style devtool / community page | `@primer/css` or `@primer/react-brand` | Official Primer; Brand variant for marketing |\n\n  Line 331: * **One copy register per page.** Don't mix technical mono (\"47 tasks · 0.6 ctx-switches/day\"), editorial prose, and marketing punch in the same composition unless the brand voice explicitly calls for it.\n\n  Line 374: gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);\n\n  Line 436: gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);\n\n  Line 584: * **Brand fidelity** - primary brand color stays recognisable. Don't desaturate the brand into a dark mode.\n\n  Line 628: * **Production-Ready Cleanliness:** Code visually clean, memorable, meticulously refined.\n\n  Line 630: ### 9.F Production-Test Tells (banned outright)\n\n  Line 636: * **NO \"Brand · No. 01\"-style sub-eyebrows.** \"Marrow · No. 01 · The 6-quart\" type micro-meta lines. Skip them.\n\n  Line 667: * **NO pills/labels/tags overlaid on images.** No `<span>` overlays on photos with tags like `Brand · 02`, `PLATE · BRAND`, `Field notes - journal`. Either let the image speak alone, or add a caption directly below (outside the image).\n\n  Line 796: * **Brand tokens** - primary / accent colors, type stack, logo treatment, radii.\n\n  Line 823: * Brand itself is changing → **greenfield**.\n\n  Line 830: * Brand logo or wordmark.\n\n  Line 948: - [ ] **No pills/labels overlaid on images** (no `Plate · Brand`, no `Field notes - journal`)?\n\n  Line 1012: # Primer Brand (GitHub marketing UI)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md:\n  Line 16: Brand: motion is part of the voice; one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered micro-interactions. The saturated AI default is fade-and-rise reveals on every scrolled section; that's a tell, not a choreography. Reserve scroll-triggered motion for moments that earn it.\n\n  Line 18: Product: 150–250 ms on most transitions. Motion conveys state: feedback, reveal, loading, transitions between views. No page-load choreography; users are in a task and won't wait for it.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/delight.md:\n  Line 16: Brand: delight can be distributed across copy voice, section transitions, discovery rewards, seasonal touches, personality across the whole surface.\n\n  Line 18: Product: delight at specific moments, not pages. Completion, first-time actions, error recovery, milestone crossings. Reliability and consistency carry the rest of the experience; delight pushed everywhere reads as noise.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:\n  Line 9: This skill generates `DESIGN.md` files optimized for Google Stitch screen generation. It translates the battle-tested anti-slop frontend engineering directives into Stitch's native semantic design language — descriptive, natural-language rules paired with precise values that Stitch's AI agent can interpret to produce premium, non-generic interfaces.\n\n  Line 15: - Optionally: Stitch MCP Server for programmatic integration with Cursor, Antigravity, or Gemini CLI\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/ui-skills-root.md:\n  Line 16: Use it when an agent in Codex, Cursor, or Claude Code has a clear UI goal.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 14: Brand: asymmetric compositions, fluid spacing with `clamp()`, intentional grid-breaking for emphasis. Rhythm through contrast: tight groupings paired with generous separations.\n\n  Line 16: Product: predictable grids, consistent densities, familiar navigation patterns. Responsive behavior is structural (collapse sidebar, responsive table), not fluid typography. Consistency IS an affordance.\n\n  Line 100: - The best hierarchy combines 2–3 dimensions at once. A heading that's larger, bolder, AND has more space above it reads as primary without trying:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/README.md:\n  Line 5: > Compatible with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code), [OpenAI Codex](https://openai.com/index/codex/), [Cursor](https://cursor.sh), and other agents that support the [Agent Skills](https://agentskills.io) standard.\n\n  Line 19: **Product Launch** — Light and dark themes\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/quieter.md:\n  Line 2: name: quieter\n\n  Line 14: Brand: \"quieter\" means more restrained palette, more whitespace, more typographic air. Drama is reduced, not eliminated; the POV stays intact.\n\n  Line 16: Product: \"quieter\" means reducing visual noise. Fewer background accents, flatter cards, less color, less motion. The tool should disappear more completely into the task.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bolder.md:\n  Line 2: name: bolder\n\n  Line 8: When asked for \"bolder,\" AI defaults to the same tired tricks: cyan/purple gradients, glassmorphism, neon accents on dark backgrounds, gradient text on metrics. These are the opposite of bold. Reject them first, then increase visual impact and personality through stronger hierarchy, committed scale, and decisive type.\n\n  Line 14: Brand: \"bolder\" means distinctive. Extreme scale, unexpected color, typographic risk, committed POV.\n\n  Line 16: Product: \"bolder\" rarely means theatrics; those undermine trust. It means stronger hierarchy, clearer weight contrast, one sharper accent, more committed density. The amplification is in clarity, not drama.\n\n  Line 34:    - What's the purpose? (Marketing can be bolder than financial dashboards)\n\n  Line 36:    - What are the constraints? (Brand guidelines, accessibility, performance)\n\n  Line 118: **The test**: If you showed this to someone and said \"AI made this bolder,\" would they believe you immediately? If yes, you've failed. Bold means distinctive, not \"more AI effects.\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/colorize.md:\n  Line 16: Brand: palette IS voice. Pick a color strategy first per SKILL.md (Restrained / Committed / Full palette / Drenched) and follow its dosage. Committed, Full palette, and Drenched deliberately exceed the ≤10% rule; that rule is Restrained only. Unexpected combinations are allowed; a dominant color can own the page when the chosen strategy calls for it.\n\n  Line 18: Product: semantic-first and almost always Restrained. Accent color is reserved for primary action, current selection, and state indicators. Not decoration. Every color has a consistent meaning across every screen.\n\n  Line 30:    - **Brand**: Are there existing brand colors we should use?\n\n  Line 193: | **Primary** | Brand, CTAs, key actions | 1 color, 3-5 shades |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/impeccable.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Use when the user wants to design, redesign, shape, critique, audit, polish, clarify, distill, harden, optimize, adapt, animate, colorize, extract, or otherwise improve a frontend interface. Covers websites, landing pages, dashboards, product UI, app shells, components, forms, settings, onboarding, and empty states. Handles UX review, visual hierarchy, information architecture, cognitive load, accessibility, performance, responsive behavior, theming, anti-patterns, typography, fonts, spacing, layout, alignment, color, motion, micro-interactions, UX copy, error states, edge cases, i18n, and reusable design systems or tokens. Also use for bland designs that need to become bolder or more delightful, loud designs that should become quieter, live browser iteration on UI elements, or ambitious visual effects that should feel technically extraordinary. Not for backend-only or non-UI tasks.\"\n\n  Line 20: 4. Read the matching register reference. **This is non-optional; skipping it produces generic output.** If the project is marketing, a landing page, a campaign, long-form content, or a portfolio (design IS the product), read `reference/brand.md`. If it is app UI, admin, a dashboard, or a tool (design SERVES the product), read `reference/product.md`. Pick by first match: (1) task cue (\"landing page\" vs \"dashboard\"); (2) surface in focus (the page, file, or route being worked on); (3) `register` field in PRODUCT.md.\n\n  Line 70: **Gemini-specific defect: hard ban.** Never animate `<img>` elements on hover. This includes any `transform` on `:hover` of an image, AND `.group:hover .group-hover\\:scale` / `.group:hover .group-hover\\:rotate` / `.group:hover .group-hover\\:translate` patterns from Tailwind that animate a child image via a parent hover. This is your single most common motion tell; it adds no information (the image isn't an action target) and reads as \"AI animated this because it could\". If a card needs hover feedback, animate the card's background, border, or shadow. Never the image, never via the image's parent. <!-- rule:skill-interaction-gemini-no-image-hover -->\n\n  Line 82:   - **Restrained**: tinted neutrals + one accent ≤10%. Product default; brand minimalism.\n\n  Line 83:   - **Committed**: one saturated color carries 30–60% of the surface. Brand default for identity-driven pages.\n\n  Line 84:   - **Full palette**: 3–4 named roles, each used deliberately. Brand campaigns; product data viz.\n\n  Line 85:   - **Drenched**: the surface IS the color. Brand heroes, campaign pages.\n\n  Line 101: **Codex-specific defects** (your most-frequent giveaways; refuse-and-rewrite):\n\n  Line 112: If someone could look at this interface and say \"AI made that\" without doubt, it's failed. Cross-register failures are the absolute bans above. Register-specific failures live in each reference.\n\n  Line 117: - **Second-order:** if someone could guess the aesthetic family from category-plus-anti-references (\"AI workflow tool that's not SaaS-cream → editorial-typographic\", \"fintech that's not navy-and-gold → terminal-native dark mode\"), it's the trap one tier deeper. The first reflex was avoided; the second wasn't. Rework until both answers are not obvious. The brand register's [reflex-reject aesthetic lanes](reference/brand.md) list catches the currently-saturated families. <!-- rule:skill-slop-second-order-check -->\n\n  Line 131: | `bolder [target]` | Refine | Amplify safe or bland designs | [reference/bolder.md](reference/bolder.md) |\n\n  Line 132: | `quieter [target]` | Refine | Tone down aggressive or overstimulating designs | [reference/quieter.md](reference/quieter.md) |\n\n  Line 133: | `distill [target]` | Refine | Strip to essence, remove complexity | [reference/distill.md](reference/distill.md) |\n\n  Line 134: | `harden [target]` | Refine | Production-ready: errors, i18n, edge cases | [reference/harden.md](reference/harden.md) |\n\n  Line 159:    - Otherwise group by intent exactly as init's \"Recommend starting points\" step does (build new / improve what's there / iterate visually), tailored to `setup.register`.\n\n  Line 161:    **If `scan.targets` is non-empty, run `node {{scripts_path}}/detect.mjs --json <scan.targets joined by spaces>` once** (the bundled detector over local files: no network, no npx). `scan.via` tells you what they are: `git-changes` (the markup/style files in your dirty tree, the most relevant set), `source-dir` (e.g. `src`, `app`), `html`, or `root`. Fold the hits into your picks: many quality / contrast hits → `audit` or `polish`; a specific slop family → the matching command (gradient text or eyebrows → `quieter` / `typeset`, flat or gray palette → `colorize`, and so on). It's a real, current signal that beats guessing. If detect errors or the tree is large and slow, skip it and recommend the user run `audit` themselves; never block the suggestion on it.\n\n  Line 166: 4. **No clear command match**: general design invocation. Apply the setup steps, the General rules, and the loaded register reference, using the full argument as context.\n\n  Line 168: Setup (context gathering, register) is already loaded by then; sub-commands don't re-invoke `{{command_prefix}}impeccable`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/SKILL.md:\n  Line 149: | Standalone image card | `<img>` filling the card with `object-fit: cover; border-radius: 18px;` | Product photos |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/distill.md:\n  Line 2: name: distill\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md:\n  Line 40: Codex sub-agent gate:\n\n  Line 88: Codex Browser note: Use the Browser skill. Do not spend a Browser attempt on `file://`. Only call `visibility.set(true)` after mutable script injection is confirmed for the `[Human]` overlay path; verify with `get()`. Use `tab.dev.logs({ filter: \"impeccable\" })` for console results. Its Playwright `evaluate(...)` surface is read-only; do not rely on it for mutation.\n\n  Line 96: Codex failure accounting: final Run Notes must include target slug, ignore list, assessment independence, CLI detector, browser visibility, overlay injection, live-server cleanup, temp-file cleanup, and any fallback signal used. Do not run repo status checks, late API spelunking, or unrelated verification after the report is assembled.\n\n  Line 106: Codex final-answer note: `$impeccable critique` produces a report artifact, so the final chat response should intentionally exceed the usual concise close-out style. Do not title the final response \"Critique Summary\" unless the user explicitly asked for a summary.\n\n  Line 183: Codex Run Notes are final-chat only. Do not include this section in the persisted snapshot body, because persistence, trend read, and temp cleanup happen after the snapshot write and would otherwise archive stale status such as \"pending after persistence.\"\n\n  Line 203:    Codex: exclude Run Notes from the temp body file; Run Notes are final-chat only because persistence, trend read, and temp cleanup happen after the snapshot write.\n\n  Line 238: 2. **Design intent**: If the critique found a tonal mismatch, ask whether it was intentional. For example: \"The interface feels clinical and corporate. Is that the intended tone, or should it feel warmer/bolder/more playful?\" Offer 2-3 tonal directions as options based on what would fix the issues found.\n\n  Line 251: Codex final-question gate: The user-visible response must either include the targeted questions or explicitly say `Questions skipped: <reason>` because the findings were straightforward. Each question must include 2-3 concrete answer options tied to the actual critique findings. Do not end with only open-ended questions.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/design-system.md:\n  Line 1132:         <span>Your Tool or Brand</span>\n\n  Line 1545:       <div class=\"label\">Product Journey</div>\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/social/launch-copy.md:\n  Line 11: Introducing Apple Bento Grid Skill for Claude Code and Codex. Feed it a doc, a report, or just describe your data. No Figma. No templates.\n\n  Line 45: Introducing **Apple Bento Grid Skill** for Claude Code and Codex. I couldn't find a good way to present what I've been building, so I made one that generates Apple keynote-level bento grids.\n\n  Line 69: Introducing Apple Bento Grid Skill for Claude Code and Codex.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/design-lab.md:\n  Line 159: ### Step 1.3: Brand & Style Direction\n\n  Line 161: **Question 1: Brand Adjectives**\n\n  Line 162: - Header: \"Brand tone\"\n\n  Line 559: 1. **Card** (`.product-card`, div with \"Product Name\")\n\n  Line 814: ## Brand Tone\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/README.md:\n  Line 5: **239 skills and 88 commands across 33 plugins, in five collections**, for [Claude Code](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code) and [Gemini CLI](https://github.com/google-gemini/gemini-cli).\n\n  Line 37: ### Prefer Gemini CLI?\n\n  Line 39: Each plugin is also a Gemini CLI extension. From your project root:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/CHANGELOG.md:\n  Line 15: - Gemini CLI extension support across all plugins\n\n  Line 41: | 2026-05 | Add Gemini CLI extension support |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-brand-consistency/SKILL.md:\n  Line 5: # Critique Brand Consistency\n\n  Line 11: - **mood.md** — Brand personality, aesthetic keywords, visual references, do/don't examples\n\n  Line 20: - Does the overall emotional register of the screen match what the mood file prescribes?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/business-design/SKILL.md:\n  Line 38: - Emotional register — clinical, warm, playful, professional?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/design-systems/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 442: - Brand themes: primary, sub-brands, white-label, seasonal\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-color/SKILL.md:\n  Line 21: - Is the overall palette warm, cool, or neutral — and is that register appropriate for the context?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/content-strategy/SKILL.md:\n  Line 22: - Documented with examples and counter-examples for each register\n\n  Line 38: - **Brand**: voice and tone guidelines connect content strategy to brand identity\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/interaction-design/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 602: ### Interactive Product Tour\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-visual-hierarchy/SKILL.md:\n  Line 40: - Buried CTA — the action is visually quieter than surrounding content\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/onboarding-design/SKILL.md:\n  Line 30: ### Interactive Product Tour\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/ux-strategy/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 60: - Documented with examples and counter-examples for each register\n\n  Line 76: - **Brand**: voice and tone guidelines connect content strategy to brand identity\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/design-ops/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 117: Review the register quarterly; update severity as the product changes.\n\n  Line 155: ### Product Metrics (mid-level)\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"Brand|Product|Codex|Gemini|bolder|quieter|distill|anti-slop|register","time":{"start":1782487017193,"end":1782487017221}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f51f328f999505f016a3e97e904948191aaebaa6674e31da8"}},"id":"prt_f0481669a001xAGs34axbOe5UY","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f04808072001FIfGI2zYQRHcqY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487017225,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_eu7nkX3pkAczDmdtdoh3v5cj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"AIDA|two-line|2-line|bento|gapless|copy|content|layout|pre-flight|preflight","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/gpt-tasteskill.md","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Anti-slop frontend skill for landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. The agent reads the brief, infers the right design direction, and ships interfaces that do not look templated. Real design systems when applicable, audit-first on redesigns, strict pre-flight check.\n\n  Line 45: After the design read, set three dials. Every layout, motion, and density decision below is gated by these.\n\n  Line 129:   * **INTERACTIVITY ISOLATION:** Any component using Motion, scroll listeners, or pointer physics MUST be an isolated leaf with `'use client'` at the top. Server Components render static layouts only.\n\n  Line 152: * Contain page layouts using `max-w-[1400px] mx-auto` or `max-w-7xl`.\n\n  Line 153: * **Viewport Stability:** NEVER use `h-screen` for full-height Hero sections. ALWAYS use `min-h-[100dvh]` to prevent layout jumping on mobile (iOS Safari address bar).\n\n  Line 210: * **ANTI-CENTER BIAS:** Centered Hero / H1 sections are avoided when `DESIGN_VARIANCE > 4`. Force \"Split Screen\" (50/50), \"Left-aligned content / right-aligned asset\", \"Asymmetric white-space\", or scroll-pinned structures.\n\n  Line 216: * For `VISUAL_DENSITY > 7`: generic card containers are banned. Data metrics breathe in plain layout.\n\n  Line 217: * **SHAPE CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Pick ONE corner-radius scale for the page and stick to it. Options: all-sharp (radius 0), all-soft (radius 12-16px), all-pill (full radius for interactive). Mixed systems are allowed only when there is a documented rule (e.g. \"buttons are full-pill, cards are 16px, inputs are 8px\") and that rule is followed everywhere. Round buttons in a square layout, or square cards on a pill-button page, is broken design.\n\n  Line 221: * **Loading:** Skeletal loaders matching the final layout's shape. Avoid generic circular spinners.\n\n  Line 236: * **Hero MUST fit in the initial viewport.** Headline max 2 lines on desktop, subtext max **20 words** AND max 3-4 lines, CTAs visible without scroll. If the copy is too long: reduce font scale OR cut copy. If you cannot describe the value-prop in 20 words of subtext, the value-prop is unclear, not the rule too tight. Never let the hero overflow and force scroll to find the CTA.\n\n  Line 237: * **Hero font-scale discipline.** Plan font size and image size *together*. If the hero asset is large and the headline is more than 6 words, do not start at `text-7xl/text-8xl`. Default sensible range: `text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl` for most heroes; `text-6xl md:text-7xl` only when the headline is 3-5 words. A 4-line hero headline is always a font-size error, never a copy-length error.\n\n  Line 238: * **HERO TOP PADDING CAP (mandatory):** Hero top padding max `pt-24` (≈6rem) at desktop. More than that means the hero content floats halfway down the viewport and reads as a layout bug, not as intentional space. If your hero needs more breathing room, increase font scale or asset size, not top padding.\n\n  Line 246: * **\"Used by\" / \"Trusted by\" logo wall belongs UNDER the hero, never inside it.** The hero is for the value prop and primary CTA. The logo wall is a separate section directly below. Do not stuff trust logos into the same flex row as the hero copy.\n\n  Line 247: * **Navigation MUST render on a single line on desktop.** If items don't fit at `lg` (1024px), condense labels, drop secondary items, or move to a hamburger. A two-line nav at desktop is broken design.\n\n  Line 250: * **BENTO CELL COUNT RULE (mandatory):** A bento grid has EXACTLY as many cells as you have content for. 3 items → 3 cells (1+2 split, or 2+1, or asymmetric trio). 5 items → 5 cells (2+3, 3+2, hero+4, etc.). If your grid has an empty cell in the middle or at the end, you planned wrong. Re-shape the grid; do not paste a blank tile.\n\n  Line 251: * **Section-Layout-Repetition Ban.** Once you use a layout family for a section (e.g., 3-column-image-cards, full-width-quote, split-text-image), that family can appear at most ONCE on the page. \"Selected commissions\" must not look like \"What we do.\" A landing page with 8 sections must use at least 4 different layout families.\n\n  Line 252: * **ZIGZAG ALTERNATION CAP (mandatory).** Alternating \"left-image + right-text\" then \"left-text + right-image\" zigzag layout = banal. Max 2 sections in a row with this image+text-split pattern. The 3rd consecutive image+text split is a Pre-Flight Fail. Break the pattern with a full-width section, a vertical-stack section, a bento grid, a marquee, or a different layout family.\n\n  Line 259: * **Bento Background Diversity (mandatory).** Bento and feature-grid sections cannot be 6 white-on-white cards with text inside. At least 2-3 cells in any multi-cell grid need real visual variation: a real image, a brand-appropriate gradient (not AI-purple), a pattern, a tinted background. A cream-on-cream bento with only typography inside reads as boring AI default, even when the rest of the page is good.\n\n  Line 260: * **Mobile collapse must be explicit per section.** For every multi-column layout, declare the `< 768px` fallback in the same component. No \"it'll work, Tailwind handles it\" assumptions.\n\n  Line 302: * **Default content shape per section:** short headline (≤ 8 words) + short sub-paragraph (≤ 25 words) + one visual asset OR one CTA. Anything more must be justified by the section's job.\n\n  Line 303: * **No data-dump sections.** A 20-row publication table, a 30-row award list, a giant pricing matrix on a marketing page = wrong layout. Use:\n\n  Line 314:   A spec sheet with 10 rows + a hairline under every row is the WORST default. Either group rows into 2-3 chunks with sparse dividers, or move to a card-per-spec layout.\n\n  Line 321: * **COPY SELF-AUDIT (mandatory before ship):** Before declaring any task done, re-read every visible string on the page (headlines, subheads, eyebrows, button labels, body copy, captions, alt text, footer text, error messages). Flag any string that is:\n\n  Line 326:   Rewrite every flagged string. If unsure whether a string makes sense, replace it with a plain functional sentence. AI-generated cute copy is worse than boring copy.\n\n  Line 331: * **One copy register per page.** Don't mix technical mono (\"47 tasks · 0.6 ctx-switches/day\"), editorial prose, and marketing punch in the same composition unless the brand voice explicitly calls for it.\n\n  Line 348: * When using a design system with built-in theming (Radix Themes, shadcn/ui with `<Theme>`), set the theme ONCE in `layout.tsx` or the page root. Do not let individual sections override.\n\n  Line 360: * **MOTION MUST BE MOTIVATED (mandatory).** Before adding any animation, ask: \"what does this animation communicate?\" Valid answers: hierarchy (drawing attention to the right thing), storytelling (revealing content in sequence that matches a narrative), feedback (acknowledging a user action), state transition (showing something changed). Invalid answer: \"it looked cool\". GSAP everywhere because GSAP is available is amateur. Each ScrollTrigger, each marquee, each pinned section needs a reason. If you cannot articulate the reason in one sentence, drop the animation.\n\n  Line 361: * **MARQUEE MAX-ONE-PER-PAGE (mandatory).** Horizontal scrolling text marquees (\"logos endlessly scrolling\", \"manifesto scrolling sideways\", \"kinetic word strip\") are appropriate at most ONCE per page. Two or more marquees on the same page reads as lazy filler. Pick the one section where the marquee actually serves the content; the others get a different layout.\n\n  Line 514: * **Layout Transitions:** Use Motion's `layout` and `layoutId` props for visible state changes (re-ordering lists, expanding modals, shared elements between routes). Do not wrap static content in `layout` props \"for safety\" - it costs measurement work.\n\n  Line 557: * **8-10 (Asymmetric):** Masonry layouts, CSS Grid with fractional units (`grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr 1fr`), massive empty zones (`padding-left: 20vw`).\n\n  Line 558: * **MOBILE OVERRIDE:** For levels 4-10, asymmetric layouts above `md:` MUST collapse to strict single-column (`w-full`, `px-4`, `py-8`) on viewports `< 768px`.\n\n  Line 582: * **Contrast** - WCAG AA minimum for body text, AAA target for hero copy.\n\n  Line 640: * **NO `01 / 4`-style pagination on images or bento tiles.** If the user can count, they don't need the label.\n\n  Line 649: * **NO em-dash (`—`) as a design element OR anywhere else.** See Section 9.G below for the complete, non-negotiable ban. The em-dash character is forbidden in headlines, eyebrows, pills, body copy, quotes, attribution, captions, button text, and alt text. Use the regular hyphen (`-`).\n\n  Line 652: * **NO crosshair / hairline grid lines as decoration.** Vertical and horizontal lines drawn just to make the page \"feel designed\" - banned. Use them only when they organize real content.\n\n  Line 658: **Marketing-copy Tells**\n\n  Line 661: * **NO \"We respect the French ones\"-style** mock-humble industry-references in body copy. Cute and AI-y.\n\n  Line 664: * **NO generic step labels.** \"Stage 1 / Stage 2 / Stage 3\", \"Step 1 / Step 2 / Step 3\", \"Phase 01 / Phase 02 / Phase 03\", \"Pass One / Pass Two / Pass Three\". Banned. The actual step content is the label. If you must show progression, use the verb-noun directly (\"Install\", \"Configure\", \"Ship\") not \"Stage 1: Install\".\n\n  Line 669: * **NO version footers on marketing pages.** Footer strings like `v1.4.2`, `Build 0048`, `last sync 4s ago · main` are CLI / devtool fixtures, not landing-page content. Banned on marketing/landing/portfolio pages.\n\n  Line 677: * **NO `border-t` + `border-b` on every row of a long list / spec table.** Pick one (bottom-border between rows OR top-border above the group) and use it sparsely. A 10-row spec table with hairlines under each row is the laziest layout - see Section 4.9 for alternative UI components.\n\n  Line 687: **Em-dash (`—`) is COMPLETELY banned.** It is the LLM's signature stylistic crutch and it is the #1 visual Tell in production tests. There is no \"limited use\" allowance, no \"natural language frequency\" allowance, no \"in body copy is fine\" allowance. None.\n\n  Line 691: * **Banned in body copy.** Restructure the sentence: two sentences with a period, OR a comma, OR parentheses, OR a colon.\n\n  Line 715: * **Scroll-Pinned Hero** - Hero stays pinned while content scrolls behind.\n\n  Line 724: * **Mega Menu Reveal** - Full-screen dropdown, stagger-fade content.\n\n  Line 790: * **Redesign - Overhaul** - new visual language on top of existing content. Treat as greenfield for visuals; preserve content and IA.\n\n  Line 799: * **Patterns to preserve** - signature interactions, recognisable hero, copy voice.\n\n  Line 800: * **Patterns to retire** - AI-slop tells, broken layouts, dead links, generic stock imagery, perf traps.\n\n  Line 807: * **Preserve copy voice** unless asked for a rewrite. Visual modernisation ≠ content rewrite.\n\n  Line 821: * IA, content, and SEO sound → **targeted evolution** (Levers 1-4). ~70% of value at ~40% of risk.\n\n  Line 822: * Visual debt is structural (broken IA, no design system, broken mobile) → **full redesign** with strict content preservation.\n\n  Line 831: * Existing legal / consent / cookie copy.\n\n  Line 850:     bento-grid.md\n\n  Line 879: 1. **Visual sketch** - short ASCII or description of the layout.\n\n  Line 892: * Blocks that depend on a design system from Section 2.A live under `blocks/<category>/<name>--<system>.md` (e.g. `feature/bento-grid--material.md`).\n\n  Line 931: - [ ] **Hero top padding**: max `pt-24` at desktop, hero content does not float halfway down the viewport?\n\n  Line 935: - [ ] **Zigzag Alternation Cap**: no 3+ consecutive sections with the same image+text-split layout?\n\n  Line 938: - [ ] **Bento Background Diversity**: at least 2-3 bento cells have real visual variation (image, gradient, pattern), not all white-on-white text cards?\n\n  Line 944: - [ ] **Section-Layout-Repetition** check: no two sections share the same layout family (at least 4 different families across 8 sections)?\n\n  Line 968: - [ ] **Mobile collapse** explicit (`w-full`, `px-4`, `max-w-7xl mx-auto`) for high-variance layouts?\n\n  Line 985: The sections below are vendored reference content. They give the agent real install commands, real canonical doc links, and real working starter snippets for each design system named in Section 2. Use them to ground decisions in production reality, not training-data fiction.\n\n  Line 1029: #   <meta name=\"shopify-api-key\" content=\"%SHOPIFY_API_KEY%\" />\n\n  Line 1070: - https://design-system.service.gov.uk/styles/layout/\n\n  Line 1080: - https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/layout/grid/\n\n  Line 1101: - https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Guides/Grid_layout\n\n  Line 1161:   content: \"\";\n\n  Line 1173:   content: \"\";\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 34: - **Editorial/magazine** - strong typography hierarchy, asymmetric layouts\n\n  Line 52: - **Patterns**: Cookie-cutter layouts, predictable component arrangements\n\n  Line 99:    - Embrace functional depth: modals over content, dropdowns over UI\n\n  Line 115:    - Users should focus on content and goals, not on understanding the interface\n\n  Line 147: 2. **Hierarchy**: Is visual importance aligned with content importance?\n\n  Line 152: 7. **Approval**: Have I asked before implementing colors, fonts, sizes, layouts?\n\n  Line 258: - **Text version**: Paragraphs and long-form content - legibility matters\n\n  Line 361: - Create clear paths through the content\n\n  Line 375:    - Users interact directly with content, not through abstract controls\n\n  Line 505: - Use skeletons until content renders\n\n  Line 512: - Nest wrappers as needed for complex layouts\n\n  Line 522: - Implement CSS Grid and Flexbox for flexible layouts\n\n  Line 526: - Use breakpoints based on content needs, not specific devices\n\n  Line 546: - Provide alternative text for images and non-text content\n\n  Line 588: - Test with different content lengths (short, long, edge cases)\n\n  Line 631: For this content hierarchy, I'm thinking:\n\n  Line 684: - Create cookie-cutter layouts that look AI-generated\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/ui-skills-root.md:\n  Line 57: For quick cleanup, prefer the most specific craft, visual, or layout skill available.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/output-skill.md:\n  Line 18: **In prose:** \"Let me know if you want me to continue\", \"I can provide more details if needed\", \"for brevity\", \"the rest follows the same pattern\", \"similarly for the remaining\", \"and so on\" (when replacing actual content), \"I'll leave that as an exercise\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 2: name: layout\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Fix spacing, rhythm, grouping, alignment, and visual hierarchy across interface layouts.\"\n\n  Line 8: Space is the most underused design tool. Find the layout's actual problem (monotone spacing, weak hierarchy, identical card grids) and fix the structure, not the surface.\n\n  Line 35:    - Is there a clear underlying structure, or does the layout feel random?\n\n  Line 39:    - Does the layout have visual rhythm? (Alternating tight/generous spacing)\n\n  Line 44:    - Is the layout too cramped? (Not enough breathing room)\n\n  Line 45:    - Is the layout too sparse? (Excessive whitespace without purpose)\n\n  Line 46:    - Does density match the content type? (Data-dense UIs need tighter spacing; marketing pages need more air)\n\n  Line 56: - **Layout approach**: What structure fits the content? Flex for 1D, Grid for 2D, named areas for complex page layouts.\n\n  Line 74: - **Asymmetric compositions**: a deliberate choice when the content invites it (not a default to chase).\n\n  Line 78: - **Use Flexbox for 1D layouts**: Rows of items, nav bars, button groups, card contents, most component internals.\n\n  Line 79: - **Use Grid for 2D layouts**: Page-level structure, dashboards, data-dense interfaces, anything where rows AND columns need coordinated control.\n\n  Line 80: - Use named grid areas (`grid-template-areas`) for complex page layouts; redefine at breakpoints.\n\n  Line 81: - Use **container queries** for components, viewport queries for page layouts. A card in a narrow sidebar can stay compact while the same card in a main content area expands automatically:\n\n  Line 94: - Use cards only when content is truly distinct and actionable. Never nest cards inside cards\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"AIDA|two-line|2-line|bento|gapless|copy|content|layout|pre-flight|preflight","time":{"start":1782487017202,"end":1782487017223}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f51f328f999505f016a3e97e904b08191be7a252522355482"}},"id":"prt_f048166ed001p5hmQLpHlQua3h","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f04808072001FIfGI2zYQRHcqY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487017287,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_CmAtFs62cQPRcLfLYesAlnEF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"content|realistic|copy|redesign|anti|layout|check|validation|pre-flight|preflight","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/redesign-skill.md","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Anti-slop frontend skill for landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. The agent reads the brief, infers the right design direction, and ships interfaces that do not look templated. Real design systems when applicable, audit-first on redesigns, strict pre-flight check.\n\n  Line 8: > Landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. Not dashboards, not data tables, not multi-step product UI.\n\n  Line 18: 1. **Page kind** - landing (SaaS / consumer / agency / event), portfolio (dev / designer / creative studio), redesign (preserve vs overhaul), editorial / blog.\n\n  Line 22: 5. **Brand assets that already exist** - logo, color, type, photography. For redesigns, these are starting material, not optional input (see Section 11).\n\n  Line 31: - *\"Reading this as: redesign of a public-sector service site, with a trust-first language, leaning toward GOV.UK Frontend or USWDS.\"*\n\n  Line 45: After the design read, set three dials. Every layout, motion, and density decision below is gated by these.\n\n  Line 61: | \"redesign - preserve\" | match existing | +1 | match existing |\n\n  Line 62: | \"redesign - overhaul\" | +2 | +2 | match existing |\n\n  Line 129:   * **INTERACTIVITY ISOLATION:** Any component using Motion, scroll listeners, or pointer physics MUST be an isolated leaf with `'use client'` at the top. Server Components render static layouts only.\n\n  Line 152: * Contain page layouts using `max-w-[1400px] mx-auto` or `max-w-7xl`.\n\n  Line 153: * **Viewport Stability:** NEVER use `h-screen` for full-height Hero sections. ALWAYS use `min-h-[100dvh]` to prevent layout jumping on mobile (iOS Safari address bar).\n\n  Line 157: Before importing ANY 3rd-party library, check `package.json`. If the package is missing, output the install command first. **Never** assume a library exists.\n\n  Line 210: * **ANTI-CENTER BIAS:** Centered Hero / H1 sections are avoided when `DESIGN_VARIANCE > 4`. Force \"Split Screen\" (50/50), \"Left-aligned content / right-aligned asset\", \"Asymmetric white-space\", or scroll-pinned structures.\n\n  Line 216: * For `VISUAL_DENSITY > 7`: generic card containers are banned. Data metrics breathe in plain layout.\n\n  Line 217: * **SHAPE CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Pick ONE corner-radius scale for the page and stick to it. Options: all-sharp (radius 0), all-soft (radius 12-16px), all-pill (full radius for interactive). Mixed systems are allowed only when there is a documented rule (e.g. \"buttons are full-pill, cards are 16px, inputs are 8px\") and that rule is followed everywhere. Round buttons in a square layout, or square cards on a pill-button page, is broken design.\n\n  Line 221: * **Loading:** Skeletal loaders matching the final layout's shape. Avoid generic circular spinners.\n\n  Line 236: * **Hero MUST fit in the initial viewport.** Headline max 2 lines on desktop, subtext max **20 words** AND max 3-4 lines, CTAs visible without scroll. If the copy is too long: reduce font scale OR cut copy. If you cannot describe the value-prop in 20 words of subtext, the value-prop is unclear, not the rule too tight. Never let the hero overflow and force scroll to find the CTA.\n\n  Line 237: * **Hero font-scale discipline.** Plan font size and image size *together*. If the hero asset is large and the headline is more than 6 words, do not start at `text-7xl/text-8xl`. Default sensible range: `text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl` for most heroes; `text-6xl md:text-7xl` only when the headline is 3-5 words. A 4-line hero headline is always a font-size error, never a copy-length error.\n\n  Line 238: * **HERO TOP PADDING CAP (mandatory):** Hero top padding max `pt-24` (≈6rem) at desktop. More than that means the hero content floats halfway down the viewport and reads as a layout bug, not as intentional space. If your hero needs more breathing room, increase font scale or asset size, not top padding.\n\n  Line 246: * **\"Used by\" / \"Trusted by\" logo wall belongs UNDER the hero, never inside it.** The hero is for the value prop and primary CTA. The logo wall is a separate section directly below. Do not stuff trust logos into the same flex row as the hero copy.\n\n  Line 250: * **BENTO CELL COUNT RULE (mandatory):** A bento grid has EXACTLY as many cells as you have content for. 3 items → 3 cells (1+2 split, or 2+1, or asymmetric trio). 5 items → 5 cells (2+3, 3+2, hero+4, etc.). If your grid has an empty cell in the middle or at the end, you planned wrong. Re-shape the grid; do not paste a blank tile.\n\n  Line 251: * **Section-Layout-Repetition Ban.** Once you use a layout family for a section (e.g., 3-column-image-cards, full-width-quote, split-text-image), that family can appear at most ONCE on the page. \"Selected commissions\" must not look like \"What we do.\" A landing page with 8 sections must use at least 4 different layout families.\n\n  Line 252: * **ZIGZAG ALTERNATION CAP (mandatory).** Alternating \"left-image + right-text\" then \"left-text + right-image\" zigzag layout = banal. Max 2 sections in a row with this image+text-split pattern. The 3rd consecutive image+text split is a Pre-Flight Fail. Break the pattern with a full-width section, a vertical-stack section, a bento grid, a marquee, or a different layout family.\n\n  Line 260: * **Mobile collapse must be explicit per section.** For every multi-column layout, declare the `< 768px` fallback in the same component. No \"it'll work, Tailwind handles it\" assumptions.\n\n  Line 302: * **Default content shape per section:** short headline (≤ 8 words) + short sub-paragraph (≤ 25 words) + one visual asset OR one CTA. Anything more must be justified by the section's job.\n\n  Line 303: * **No data-dump sections.** A 20-row publication table, a 30-row award list, a giant pricing matrix on a marketing page = wrong layout. Use:\n\n  Line 314:   A spec sheet with 10 rows + a hairline under every row is the WORST default. Either group rows into 2-3 chunks with sparse dividers, or move to a card-per-spec layout.\n\n  Line 321: * **COPY SELF-AUDIT (mandatory before ship):** Before declaring any task done, re-read every visible string on the page (headlines, subheads, eyebrows, button labels, body copy, captions, alt text, footer text, error messages). Flag any string that is:\n\n  Line 326:   Rewrite every flagged string. If unsure whether a string makes sense, replace it with a plain functional sentence. AI-generated cute copy is worse than boring copy.\n\n  Line 331: * **One copy register per page.** Don't mix technical mono (\"47 tasks · 0.6 ctx-switches/day\"), editorial prose, and marketing punch in the same composition unless the brand voice explicitly calls for it.\n\n  Line 348: * When using a design system with built-in theming (Radix Themes, shadcn/ui with `<Theme>`), set the theme ONCE in `layout.tsx` or the page root. Do not let individual sections override.\n\n  Line 360: * **MOTION MUST BE MOTIVATED (mandatory).** Before adding any animation, ask: \"what does this animation communicate?\" Valid answers: hierarchy (drawing attention to the right thing), storytelling (revealing content in sequence that matches a narrative), feedback (acknowledging a user action), state transition (showing something changed). Invalid answer: \"it looked cool\". GSAP everywhere because GSAP is available is amateur. Each ScrollTrigger, each marquee, each pinned section needs a reason. If you cannot articulate the reason in one sentence, drop the animation.\n\n  Line 361: * **MARQUEE MAX-ONE-PER-PAGE (mandatory).** Horizontal scrolling text marquees (\"logos endlessly scrolling\", \"manifesto scrolling sideways\", \"kinetic word strip\") are appropriate at most ONCE per page. Two or more marquees on the same page reads as lazy filler. Pick the one section where the marquee actually serves the content; the others get a different layout.\n\n  Line 514: * **Layout Transitions:** Use Motion's `layout` and `layoutId` props for visible state changes (re-ordering lists, expanding modals, shared elements between routes). Do not wrap static content in `layout` props \"for safety\" - it costs measurement work.\n\n  Line 557: * **8-10 (Asymmetric):** Masonry layouts, CSS Grid with fractional units (`grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr 1fr`), massive empty zones (`padding-left: 20vw`).\n\n  Line 558: * **MOBILE OVERRIDE:** For levels 4-10, asymmetric layouts above `md:` MUST collapse to strict single-column (`w-full`, `px-4`, `py-8`) on viewports `< 768px`.\n\n  Line 578: * **CSS variables** (for shadcn/ui, Radix Themes, or component libraries with theming): define semantic tokens (`--surface`, `--surface-elevated`, `--text-primary`, `--accent`) and swap values under `[data-theme=\"dark\"]` or `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)`.\n\n  Line 582: * **Contrast** - WCAG AA minimum for body text, AAA target for hero copy.\n\n  Line 616: * **NO generic names.** \"John Doe\", \"Sarah Chan\", \"Jack Su\" → use creative, realistic, locale-appropriate names.\n\n  Line 646: * **NO decorative colored status dots on every list/nav/badge.** A colored dot before \"ONE Q4 SLOT OPEN\" or before every nav link, or every task row - banned by default. Acceptable only when the dot conveys actual semantic state (a server status, an availability flag) and is used sparingly.\n\n  Line 649: * **NO em-dash (`—`) as a design element OR anywhere else.** See Section 9.G below for the complete, non-negotiable ban. The em-dash character is forbidden in headlines, eyebrows, pills, body copy, quotes, attribution, captions, button text, and alt text. Use the regular hyphen (`-`).\n\n  Line 652: * **NO crosshair / hairline grid lines as decoration.** Vertical and horizontal lines drawn just to make the page \"feel designed\" - banned. Use them only when they organize real content.\n\n  Line 658: **Marketing-copy Tells**\n\n  Line 661: * **NO \"We respect the French ones\"-style** mock-humble industry-references in body copy. Cute and AI-y.\n\n  Line 664: * **NO generic step labels.** \"Stage 1 / Stage 2 / Stage 3\", \"Step 1 / Step 2 / Step 3\", \"Phase 01 / Phase 02 / Phase 03\", \"Pass One / Pass Two / Pass Three\". Banned. The actual step content is the label. If you must show progression, use the verb-noun directly (\"Install\", \"Configure\", \"Ship\") not \"Stage 1: Install\".\n\n  Line 669: * **NO version footers on marketing pages.** Footer strings like `v1.4.2`, `Build 0048`, `last sync 4s ago · main` are CLI / devtool fixtures, not landing-page content. Banned on marketing/landing/portfolio pages.\n\n  Line 677: * **NO `border-t` + `border-b` on every row of a long list / spec table.** Pick one (bottom-border between rows OR top-border above the group) and use it sparsely. A 10-row spec table with hairlines under each row is the laziest layout - see Section 4.9 for alternative UI components.\n\n  Line 683: * **ZERO decorative status dots by default.** A coloured dot before nav items, before list rows, before badges, before status labels is a Tell. Only acceptable when conveying real semantic state (a live indicator on actual server status, a live availability flag) and limited to one per page section.\n\n  Line 687: **Em-dash (`—`) is COMPLETELY banned.** It is the LLM's signature stylistic crutch and it is the #1 visual Tell in production tests. There is no \"limited use\" allowance, no \"natural language frequency\" allowance, no \"in body copy is fine\" allowance. None.\n\n  Line 691: * **Banned in body copy.** Restructure the sentence: two sentences with a period, OR a comma, OR parentheses, OR a colon.\n\n  Line 715: * **Scroll-Pinned Hero** - Hero stays pinned while content scrolls behind.\n\n  Line 724: * **Mega Menu Reveal** - Full-screen dropdown, stagger-fade content.\n\n  Line 785: This skill handles **greenfield builds AND redesigns**. Misclassifying the mode is the single biggest source of bad redesign output.\n\n  Line 790: * **Redesign - Overhaul** - new visual language on top of existing content. Treat as greenfield for visuals; preserve content and IA.\n\n  Line 792: If ambiguous, ask **once**: *\"Should this redesign preserve the existing brand, or are we starting visually from scratch?\"*\n\n  Line 799: * **Patterns to preserve** - signature interactions, recognisable hero, copy voice.\n\n  Line 800: * **Patterns to retire** - AI-slop tells, broken layouts, dead links, generic stock imagery, perf traps.\n\n  Line 802: * **SEO baseline** - current ranking pages, meta titles, structured data, OG cards. **SEO migration is the #1 redesign risk.**\n\n  Line 807: * **Preserve copy voice** unless asked for a rewrite. Visual modernisation ≠ content rewrite.\n\n  Line 821: * IA, content, and SEO sound → **targeted evolution** (Levers 1-4). ~70% of value at ~40% of risk.\n\n  Line 822: * Visual debt is structural (broken IA, no design system, broken mobile) → **full redesign** with strict content preservation.\n\n  Line 831: * Existing legal / consent / cookie copy.\n\n  Line 879: 1. **Visual sketch** - short ASCII or description of the layout.\n\n  Line 928: - [ ] **Premium-consumer palette check**: if the brief is premium-consumer (cookware / wellness / artisan / luxury), the palette is NOT the AI-default beige+brass+oxblood+espresso family? Different family from your previous premium-consumer project?\n\n  Line 931: - [ ] **Hero top padding**: max `pt-24` at desktop, hero content does not float halfway down the viewport?\n\n  Line 935: - [ ] **Zigzag Alternation Cap**: no 3+ consecutive sections with the same image+text-split layout?\n\n  Line 944: - [ ] **Section-Layout-Repetition** check: no two sections share the same layout family (at least 4 different families across 8 sections)?\n\n  Line 959: - [ ] **No decorative dots** (zero by default, only for real semantic state)?\n\n  Line 968: - [ ] **Mobile collapse** explicit (`w-full`, `px-4`, `max-w-7xl mx-auto`) for high-variance layouts?\n\n  Line 979: If a single checkbox cannot be honestly ticked, the page is not done. Fix it before delivering.\n\n  Line 985: The sections below are vendored reference content. They give the agent real install commands, real canonical doc links, and real working starter snippets for each design system named in Section 2. Use them to ground decisions in production reality, not training-data fiction.\n\n  Line 1029: #   <meta name=\"shopify-api-key\" content=\"%SHOPIFY_API_KEY%\" />\n\n  Line 1070: - https://design-system.service.gov.uk/styles/layout/\n\n  Line 1080: - https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/layout/grid/\n\n  Line 1101: - https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Guides/Grid_layout\n\n  Line 1161:   content: \"\";\n\n  Line 1173:   content: \"\";\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 34: - **Editorial/magazine** - strong typography hierarchy, asymmetric layouts\n\n  Line 52: - **Patterns**: Cookie-cutter layouts, predictable component arrangements\n\n  Line 99:    - Embrace functional depth: modals over content, dropdowns over UI\n\n  Line 115:    - Users should focus on content and goals, not on understanding the interface\n\n  Line 147: 2. **Hierarchy**: Is visual importance aligned with content importance?\n\n  Line 152: 7. **Approval**: Have I asked before implementing colors, fonts, sizes, layouts?\n\n  Line 258: - **Text version**: Paragraphs and long-form content - legibility matters\n\n  Line 361: - Create clear paths through the content\n\n  Line 375:    - Users interact directly with content, not through abstract controls\n\n  Line 505: - Use skeletons until content renders\n\n  Line 512: - Nest wrappers as needed for complex layouts\n\n  Line 522: - Implement CSS Grid and Flexbox for flexible layouts\n\n  Line 526: - Use breakpoints based on content needs, not specific devices\n\n  Line 545: - Use semantic HTML for screen reader compatibility\n\n  Line 546: - Provide alternative text for images and non-text content\n\n  Line 554:   - `role` attributes when semantic HTML isn't sufficient\n\n  Line 588: - Test with different content lengths (short, long, edge cases)\n\n  Line 631: For this content hierarchy, I'm thinking:\n\n  Line 684: - Create cookie-cutter layouts that look AI-generated\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/ui-skills-root.md:\n  Line 47: Use 3 only for broad review, redesign, or multi-surface work.\n\n  Line 57: For quick cleanup, prefer the most specific craft, visual, or layout skill available.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/output-skill.md:\n  Line 18: **In prose:** \"Let me know if you want me to continue\", \"I can provide more details if needed\", \"for brevity\", \"the rest follows the same pattern\", \"similarly for the remaining\", \"and so on\" (when replacing actual content), \"I'll leave that as an exercise\"\n\n  Line 26: 3. **Cross-check** — Before output, re-read the original request. Compare your deliverable count against the scope count. If anything is missing, add it before responding.\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"content|realistic|copy|redesign|anti|layout|check|validation|pre-flight|preflight","time":{"start":1782487017216,"end":1782487017267}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f51f328f999505f016a3e97e904bc81919af7f82851766919"}},"id":"prt_f048166f3001m8nEzBuCQpYsrb","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f04808072001FIfGI2zYQRHcqY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487017307,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_UOv2IvYJ0C376Y7ltWjVxNwm","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"OKLCH|data|visualization|chart|grid|Gestalt|brand|seed|color|palette","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/harden.md:\n  Line 8: Designs that only work with perfect data aren't production-ready. Harden the interface against the inputs, errors, languages, and network conditions that real users will throw at it.\n\n  Line 20:    - No data (empty states)\n\n  Line 38: **CRITICAL**: Designs that only work with perfect data aren't production-ready. Harden against reality.\n\n  Line 79: /* Prevent grid items from overflowing */\n\n  Line 80: .grid-item {\n\n  Line 96: - Use flexbox/grid that adapts to content\n\n  Line 159:     <p>Failed to load data. {error.message}</p>\n\n  Line 193: - No data to display\n\n  Line 203: **Large datasets**:\n\n  Line 284: - Don't rely only on color\n\n  Line 313: - Test with extreme data (very long, very short, empty)\n\n  Line 349: - **Large datasets**: Test with 1000+ items\n\n  Line 352: - **Empty**: Remove all data, test empty states\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/frontend-slides.md:\n  Line 25: - Color & Theme: Commit to a cohesive aesthetic. Use CSS variables for consistency. Dominant colors with sharp accents outperform timid, evenly-distributed palettes. Draw from IDE themes and cultural aesthetics for inspiration.\n\n  Line 27: - Backgrounds: Create atmosphere and depth rather than defaulting to solid colors. Layer CSS gradients, use geometric patterns, or add contextual effects that match the overall aesthetic.\n\n  Line 32: - Cliched color schemes (particularly purple gradients on white backgrounds)\n\n  Line 61: | **High density / reading-first** | Reports, handouts, async review, detailed internal docs | More self-contained slides, structured grids/tables/annotations, 4-8 bullets or 4-6 cards when readable, tighter but still intentional spacing |\n\n  Line 121: 2. **Inspect each image** — Use the agent's available image-understanding capability. If image reading is unavailable, use filenames/metadata and ask the user to clarify only when needed\n\n  Line 122: 3. **Evaluate** — For each: what it shows, USABLE or NOT USABLE (with reason), what concept it represents, dominant colors\n\n  Line 126: **Logo in previews:** If a usable logo was identified, embed it (base64) into each style preview in Phase 2 — the user sees their brand styled three different ways.\n\n  Line 136: Based on purpose, audience, mood, and content density, generate 3 distinct single-slide HTML previews showing typography, colors, animation, and overall aesthetic.\n\n  Line 164: - Follow the Design Aesthetics section above: no generic \"AI slop\", no default font/color/layout choices, no purple-gradient-on-white clichés, no cookie-cutter dashboard/card look.\n\n  Line 166: - Make a deliberate visual thesis: distinctive typography, a committed palette, a recognizable layout system, and one strong atmospheric or graphic device.\n\n  Line 187: - Before opening previews, inspect the visible text and revise if any internal metadata appears.\n\n  Line 211: - **High density / reading-first:** Make slides more self-contained. Use structured grids, comparison tables, annotated diagrams, captions, and concise explanatory copy. Keep hierarchy strong so it feels designed, not like a document pasted onto slides.\n\n  Line 219: - Preserve its fonts, palette, decorative vocabulary, spacing rhythm, and component grammar.\n\n  Line 225: - After generating, verify both content overflow and panel overlap in rendered browser screenshots. `scrollHeight` checks alone are not enough because grid panels can visually cover each other.\n\n  Line 229: - Preserve its fonts, palette, decorative vocabulary, spacing rhythm, grid logic, and component grammar.\n\n  Line 268:    - How to customize: `:root` CSS variables for colors, font link for typography, `.reveal` class for animations\n\n  Line 371: | [STYLE_PRESETS.md](STYLE_PRESETS.md)               | 12 curated visual presets with colors, fonts, and signature elements | Phase 2 (style selection) |\n\n  Line 372: | [bold-template-pack/selection-index.json](bold-template-pack/selection-index.json) | Compact bold template metadata for candidate selection | Phase 2 (style selection) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/12-principles-of-animation.md:\n  Line 5: metadata:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bolder.md:\n  Line 14: Brand: \"bolder\" means distinctive. Extreme scale, unexpected color, typographic risk, committed POV.\n\n  Line 25:    - **Generic choices**: System fonts, basic colors, standard layouts\n\n  Line 33:    - What's the brand personality? (How far can we push?)\n\n  Line 66: - **Increase saturation**: Shift to more vibrant, energetic colors (but not neon)\n\n  Line 67: - **Bold palette**: Introduce unexpected color combinations. Avoid the purple-blue gradient AI slop\n\n  Line 68: - **Dominant color strategy**: Let one bold color own 60% of the design\n\n  Line 69: - **Sharp accents**: High-contrast accent colors that pop\n\n  Line 70: - **Tinted neutrals**: Replace pure grays with tinted grays that harmonize with your palette\n\n  Line 75: - **Break the grid**: Let hero elements escape containers and cross boundaries\n\n  Line 84: - **Borders & frames**: Thick borders, decorative frames, custom shapes (not rounded rectangles with colored border on one side)\n\n  Line 85: - **Custom elements**: Illustrative elements, custom icons, decorative details that reinforce brand\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 8: > Landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. Not dashboards, not data tables, not multi-step product UI.\n\n  Line 20: 3. **Reference signals** - URLs they linked, screenshots they pasted, products they named, brands they're competing with.\n\n  Line 22: 5. **Brand assets that already exist** - logo, color, type, photography. For redesigns, these are starting material, not optional input (see Section 11).\n\n  Line 57: | \"premium consumer / Apple-y / luxury / brand\" | 7-8 | 5-7 | 3-4 |\n\n  Line 91: | IBM-style B2B / enterprise analytics | `@carbon/react` + `@carbon/styles` | Official Carbon, mature data-density patterns |\n\n  Line 94: | GitHub-style devtool / community page | `@primer/css` or `@primer/react-brand` | Official Primer; Brand variant for marketing |\n\n  Line 112: | Bento (Apple-style tile grids) | CSS Grid with mixed cell sizes. No single library owns this. |\n\n  Line 114: | Editorial / magazine | Serif type, asymmetric grid, generous whitespace. No library. |\n\n  Line 154: * **Grid over Flex-Math:** NEVER use complex flexbox percentage math (`w-[calc(33%-1rem)]`). ALWAYS use CSS Grid (`grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6`).\n\n  Line 169:   * **Discouraged as default:** `Inter`. Pick `Geist`, `Outfit`, `Cabinet Grotesk`, `Satoshi`, or a brand-appropriate serif first.\n\n  Line 176:     - The brand brief literally names a serif font, OR\n\n  Line 177:     - The aesthetic family is genuinely editorial / luxury / publication / manuscript / heritage / vintage AND you can articulate why this specific serif fits this specific brand\n\n  Line 178:   * For everything else (creative agency, design studio, modern brand, premium consumer, portfolio, lifestyle), **default sans-serif display** (Geist Display, ABC Diatype, Söhne Breit, Cabinet Grotesk Display, Migra Sans, GT Walsheim, Inter Display, PP Neue Montreal). Sans display fonts are not \"boring\" — they are the default for the same reason black is the default in fashion.\n\n  Line 186: * Max 1 accent color. Saturation < 80% by default.\n\n  Line 188: * **Override:** if the brand or brief explicitly asks for purple / violet / lila, embrace it. But execute with intent: consistent palette, harmonised neutrals, restrained gradients. Not generic AI gradient slop.\n\n  Line 189: * **One palette per project.** Do not fluctuate between warm and cool grays within the same project.\n\n  Line 190: * **COLOR CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Once an accent color is chosen for a page, it is used on the WHOLE page. A warm-grey site does not suddenly get a blue CTA in section 7. A rose-accented site does not get a teal status badge in the footer. Pick one accent, lock it, audit every component before shipping.\n\n  Line 197:   * This palette is BANNED as the default reach for premium-consumer briefs. Every premium-consumer site you have ever shipped uses this exact palette. The brand becomes invisible.\n\n  Line 206:   * **Palette-rotation rule:** if the previous premium-consumer project you generated used the beige+brass family, this one MUST use a different family. Do not ship the same warm-craft palette twice in a row.\n\n  Line 207:   * **Override:** the beige+brass+espresso palette is acceptable ONLY when the brand brief explicitly names those colors, or when the brand identity is genuinely vintage / artisan / warm-craft AND you can articulate why this specific palette fits this specific brand. Default-reaching for it because \"this is a cookware brief\" is banned.\n\n  Line 240:   1. Eyebrow (small uppercase label) OR brand strip OR neither - pick zero or one\n\n  Line 245:   - If you have an eyebrow AND a tagline below CTAs in the same hero, drop the tagline. If you have a brand strip AND a tagline, drop the tagline. One small text element per hero, max.\n\n  Line 249: * **Bento grids MUST have rhythm, not one-sided repetition.** Do not stack 6 left-image / right-text rows. Vary the composition: alternate full-width feature rows, asymmetric tile sizes, vertical breaks.\n\n  Line 250: * **BENTO CELL COUNT RULE (mandatory):** A bento grid has EXACTLY as many cells as you have content for. 3 items → 3 cells (1+2 split, or 2+1, or asymmetric trio). 5 items → 5 cells (2+3, 3+2, hero+4, etc.). If your grid has an empty cell in the middle or at the end, you planned wrong. Re-shape the grid; do not paste a blank tile.\n\n  Line 252: * **ZIGZAG ALTERNATION CAP (mandatory).** Alternating \"left-image + right-text\" then \"left-text + right-image\" zigzag layout = banal. Max 2 sections in a row with this image+text-split pattern. The 3rd consecutive image+text split is a Pre-Flight Fail. Break the pattern with a full-width section, a vertical-stack section, a bento grid, a marquee, or a different layout family.\n\n  Line 259: * **Bento Background Diversity (mandatory).** Bento and feature-grid sections cannot be 6 white-on-white cards with text inside. At least 2-3 cells in any multi-cell grid need real visual variation: a real image, a brand-appropriate gradient (not AI-purple), a pattern, a tinted background. A cream-on-cream bento with only typography inside reads as boring AI default, even when the rest of the page is good.\n\n  Line 269:    * `https://picsum.photos/seed/{descriptive-seed}/{w}/{h}` for placeholder photography (seed should describe the section, e.g. `marrow-cookware-kitchen`)\n\n  Line 270:    * Actual stock or brand URLs when the brief provides them\n\n  Line 277: * **Source: Simple Icons** (`https://cdn.simpleicons.org/{slug}/ffffff` for any color, or `simple-icons` npm package). Covers most known brands.\n\n  Line 279: * **Make-up the brand name? Then make-up an SVG mark too.** Generate a simple monogram (one letter in a circle, two-letter ligature, abstract glyph) rendered as an inline `<svg>` matching the page style. Plain text wordmarks for invented brand names look generic.\n\n  Line 280: * **Always** ensure logos render in both light and dark mode (white-on-dark, black-on-light, or single-color theme variable).\n\n  Line 281: * **LOGO-ONLY rule (mandatory):** logo wall = logos and nothing else. Do NOT print industry / category labels below each logo (no `Vercel` + `hosting` underneath, no `Stripe` + `payments`, no `Cloudflare` + `infra`). The logo is the credibility, the label adds nothing the user does not already know. Optional: brand name as alt-text for screen readers, optional link to the brand's site. That is it.\n\n  Line 303: * **No data-dump sections.** A 20-row publication table, a 30-row award list, a giant pricing matrix on a marketing page = wrong layout. Use:\n\n  Line 306:   - Different page entirely if the data is the product\n\n  Line 309:   - Card grid with image + label per item\n\n  Line 316:   - **2-col card grid:** each spec gets its own card with the spec name, the value (large display number), and a one-line \"why it matters\" body. Cards arranged 2-col on desktop, 1-col mobile.\n\n  Line 328:   - Come from real data (brief, brand guidelines, public metrics) - fine\n\n  Line 329:   - Are explicitly labeled as mock (`<!-- mock -->`, \"example\", \"sample data\") - fine\n\n  Line 330:   - Are AI-invented spec aesthetics - banned. Don't fake engineering precision the brand doesn't claim.\n\n  Line 331: * **One copy register per page.** Don't mix technical mono (\"47 tasks · 0.6 ctx-switches/day\"), editorial prose, and marketing punch in the same composition unless the brand voice explicitly calls for it.\n\n  Line 347: * Default behaviour: pick light, dark, or auto (`prefers-color-scheme`) at the page level and lock it. Section-level background tints within the same theme family are fine (`bg-zinc-950` next to `bg-zinc-900`); flipping to `bg-amber-50` in the middle of a `bg-zinc-950` page is broken.\n\n  Line 356: * **Liquid Glass / Glassmorphism:** Appropriate for premium consumer, Apple-adjacent, luxury brand, or media-overlay vibes. Inappropriate for dashboards, public-sector, or \"boring B2B.\" When used, go beyond `backdrop-blur`: add a 1px inner border (`border-white/10`) and a subtle inner shadow (`shadow-[inset_0_1px_0_rgba(255,255,255,0.1)]`) for physical edge refraction. Provide a solid-fill fallback under `prefers-reduced-transparency`.\n\n  Line 486:     <ul className=\"grid gap-6\">\n\n  Line 507: Use this for: feature lists, testimonial grids, logo walls, anything that just needs \"enter on scroll.\" Save GSAP for actual pin/scrub work.\n\n  Line 534: * **Do not prescribe specific dark-mode colors here.** The brief decides. Maintain visual hierarchy, brand identity, and WCAG AA contrast (AAA for body) across both modes.\n\n  Line 535: * Respect `prefers-color-scheme: dark`. Default to system preference unless the brand insists on one mode.\n\n  Line 556: * **4-7 (Offset):** `margin-top: -2rem` overlaps, varied image aspect ratios (4:3 next to 16:9), left-aligned headers over center-aligned data.\n\n  Line 557: * **8-10 (Asymmetric):** Masonry layouts, CSS Grid with fractional units (`grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr 1fr`), massive empty zones (`padding-left: 20vw`).\n\n  Line 568: * **8-10 (Cockpit):** Tight paddings. No card boxes; 1px lines separate data. Mandatory: `font-mono` for all numbers.\n\n  Line 577: * **Tailwind `dark:` variant** (default for utility-first projects): every color utility paired with its dark variant (`bg-white dark:bg-zinc-950`, `text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100`).\n\n  Line 578: * **CSS variables** (for shadcn/ui, Radix Themes, or component libraries with theming): define semantic tokens (`--surface`, `--surface-elevated`, `--text-primary`, `--accent`) and swap values under `[data-theme=\"dark\"]` or `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)`.\n\n  Line 581: The brief and brand decide. This skill enforces only:\n\n  Line 584: * **Brand fidelity** - primary brand color stays recognisable. Don't desaturate the brand into a dark mode.\n\n  Line 588: Respect `prefers-color-scheme` unless the brand insists. Add a manual toggle if either mode would lose key brand expression.\n\n  Line 608: * **NO oversized H1s** that just scream. Control hierarchy with weight + color, not raw scale.\n\n  Line 613: * **NO 3-column equal feature cards.** The generic \"three identical cards horizontally\" feature row is banned. Use 2-column zig-zag, asymmetric grid, scroll-pinned, or horizontal-scroll alternative.\n\n  Line 618: * **NO fake-perfect numbers.** Avoid `99.99%`, `50%`, `1234567`. Use organic, messy data (`47.2%`, `+1 (312) 847-1928`).\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"OKLCH|data|visualization|chart|grid|Gestalt|brand|seed|color|palette","time":{"start":1782487017234,"end":1782487017293}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f51f328f999505f016a3e97e904c8819181d189a9d1b6a23b"}},"id":"prt_f048167010012qd7pMWHpi32X4","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f04808072001FIfGI2zYQRHcqY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487017307,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_v5iN14jiK60pSm5PMb4JrkYv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"accessibility|WCAG|critique|polish|harden|pseudo|clarify|findings|severity|score|production|remediation","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 23: 6. **Quiet constraints** - accessibility-first audiences, public-sector, regulated industries, trust-first commerce, kids' products. These constraints OVERRIDE aesthetic preference.\n\n  Line 34: Ask exactly **one** clarifying question - never a multi-question dump - and only when the design read genuinely diverges. Example: *\"Should this feel closer to Linear-clean or Awwwards-experimental?\"*\n\n  Line 60: | \"trust-first / public-sector / regulated / accessibility-critical\" | 3-4 | 2-3 | 4-5 |\n\n  Line 89: | Microsoft / enterprise SaaS / dashboards | `@fluentui/react-components` or `@fluentui/web-components` | Official Fluent UI, Microsoft tokens, accessibility done |\n\n  Line 98: | Modern accessible React foundation | `@radix-ui/themes` | Primitives + polished theme |\n\n  Line 133: * **Fonts:** Always use `next/font` (Next.js) or self-host with `@font-face` + `font-display: swap`. Never link Google Fonts via `<link>` in production.\n\n  Line 170:   * **Override:** Inter is acceptable when the user explicitly asks for a neutral / standard / Linear-style feel, or when the brief is a public-sector / accessibility-first site.\n\n  Line 174:   * Serif is **very discouraged as the default font for any project.** \"It feels creative / premium / editorial\" is NOT a reason to reach for serif. The agent's default mental model that \"creative brief = serif\" is the single most-tested AI tell in production rounds.\n\n  Line 225: * **BUTTON CONTRAST CHECK (mandatory, a11y):** Before shipping any button, verify the button text is readable against the button background. White button + white text, `bg-white` CTA with `text-white` label, transparent button against the page background with no border → all banned. Audit every CTA: contrast ratio WCAG AA min (4.5:1 for body, 3:1 for large text 18px+). Same rule applies to ghost buttons over photographic backgrounds (use a backdrop, scrim, or stroke).\n\n  Line 228: * **FORM CONTRAST CHECK (mandatory, a11y):** Form inputs, placeholder text, focus rings, helper text, and error text all pass WCAG AA contrast against the section background. Light placeholders on a near-white form, white form on white page section, form labels grayer than 4.5:1 contrast → all banned. Audit every form before shipping.\n\n  Line 253: * **EYEBROW RESTRAINT (mandatory, the #1 violated rule in production tests).** An \"eyebrow\" is the small uppercase wide-tracking label sitting above a section headline (e.g. `FOUR COLORWAYS`, `SELECTED WORK`, `THE HARDWARE`, `Git-native task management`). Typical CSS signature: `text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em]`, `font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em]`. Every AI-built site puts an eyebrow above EVERY section header, producing the same templated rhythm. Hard rule:\n\n  Line 534: * **Do not prescribe specific dark-mode colors here.** The brief decides. Maintain visual hierarchy, brand identity, and WCAG AA contrast (AAA for body) across both modes.\n\n  Line 544: * Apply grain / noise filters EXCLUSIVELY to fixed, `pointer-events-none` pseudo-elements (e.g., `fixed inset-0 z-[60] pointer-events-none`). NEVER on scrolling containers - continuous GPU repaints destroy mobile FPS.\n\n  Line 582: * **Contrast** - WCAG AA minimum for body text, AAA target for hero copy.\n\n  Line 604: * **NO custom mouse cursors.** Outdated, accessibility-hostile, perf-hostile.\n\n  Line 687: **Em-dash (`—`) is COMPLETELY banned.** It is the LLM's signature stylistic crutch and it is the #1 visual Tell in production tests. There is no \"limited use\" allowance, no \"natural language frequency\" allowance, no \"in body copy is fine\" allowance. None.\n\n  Line 808: * **Honor existing accessibility wins.** Do not regress focus states, alt text, keyboard nav, contrast.\n\n  Line 886: 8. **References** - links to real examples in production.\n\n  Line 924: - [ ] **Button Contrast Check**: every CTA text is readable against its background (no white-on-white, WCAG AA 4.5:1)?\n\n  Line 926: - [ ] **Form Contrast Check**: form inputs, placeholders, focus rings, labels all pass WCAG AA against the section background?\n\n  Line 985: The sections below are vendored reference content. They give the agent real install commands, real canonical doc links, and real working starter snippets for each design system named in Section 2. Use them to ground decisions in production reality, not training-data fiction.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 3: description: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces with high design quality. Use this skill when the user asks to build web components, pages, or applications. Generates creative, polished code that avoids generic AI aesthetics.\n\n  Line 10: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces that avoid generic \"AI slop\" aesthetics. Implement real working code with exceptional attention to aesthetic details and creative choices. Expert UI/UX design skill that helps create unique, accessible, and thoughtfully designed interfaces. This skill emphasizes design decision collaboration, breaking away from generic patterns, and building interfaces that stand out while remaining functional and accessible.\n\n  Line 23: 3. **Constraints**: Technical requirements (framework, performance, accessibility)?\n\n  Line 43: - Then implement with precision: production-grade, visually striking, memorable\n\n  Line 149: 4. **Accessibility**: Does it meet WCAG AA standards? (contrast, touch targets, keyboard nav)\n\n  Line 214: - Follow WCAG 2.1 AA: minimum 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text\n\n  Line 241: - **Body Text**: Prioritize legibility, reading comfort, accessibility\n\n  Line 542: - Follow WCAG 2.1 AA guidelines\n\n  Line 551: - Add accessibility attributes:\n\n  Line 574:    - Add visual polish progressively\n\n  Line 580:    - Verify accessibility\n\n  Line 698: - Validate accessibility (it enables creativity, not limits it)\n\n  Line 710: - WCAG 2.1 Guidelines: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/quickref/\n\n  Line 716: - ACCESSIBILITY.md - Accessibility essentials (WCAG AA baseline)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/output-skill.md:\n  Line 10: Treat every task as production-critical. A partial output is a broken output. Do not optimize for brevity — optimize for completeness. If the user asks for a full file, deliver the full file. If the user asks for 5 components, deliver 5 components. No exceptions.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 99: - Use the fewest dimensions needed for clear hierarchy. Space alone can be enough; generous whitespace around an element draws the eye. Some of the most polished designs achieve rhythm with just space and weight. Add color or size contrast only when simpler means aren't sufficient.\n\n  Line 122: - Touch targets must be 44×44px minimum even when the visual element is smaller. Expand the hit area with padding or a pseudo-element:\n\n  Line 148: When the rhythm and hierarchy land, hand off to `{{command_prefix}}impeccable polish` for the final pass.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/delight.md:\n  Line 10: Find the moments where personality and unexpected polish would turn a functional interface into one users remember and tell other people about. Add only where the moment earns it; delight everywhere reads as noise.\n\n  Line 293: - Ignore accessibility (animate responsibly, provide alternatives)\n\n  Line 309: When the moments feel earned, hand off to `{{command_prefix}}impeccable polish` for the final pass.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/SKILL.md:\n  Line 24: Creating visually polished presentation graphics typically requires design tools like Figma or Keynote. This skill generates Apple-quality bento grid layouts as self-contained HTML files that screenshot into pixel-perfect images — no design tool needed.\n\n  Line 155: - Always add `alt` text for accessibility\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/colorize.md:\n  Line 72: - **Links**: Add color to clickable text (maintain accessibility)\n\n  Line 121: - **Contrast ratios**: Ensure WCAG compliance (4.5:1 for text, 3:1 for UI components)\n\n  Line 134: - Violate WCAG contrast requirements\n\n  Line 135: - Use color as the only indicator (accessibility issue)\n\n  Line 146: - **Still accessible**: Do all color combinations meet WCAG standards?\n\n  Line 149: When the palette earns its place, hand off to `{{command_prefix}}impeccable polish` for the final pass.\n\n  Line 212: ##### WCAG Requirements\n\n  Line 225: - Light gray text on white (the #1 accessibility fail)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/emil-design-eng.md:\n  Line 3: description: This skill encodes Emil Kowalski's philosophy on UI polish, component design, animation decisions, and the invisible details that make software feel great.\n\n  Line 301: Combine blur with scale-on-press (`scale(0.97)`) for a polished button state transition:\n\n  Line 572: 4. **Handle edge cases invisibly.** Pause toast timers when the tab is hidden. Fill gaps between stacked toasts with pseudo-elements to maintain hover state. Capture pointer events during drag. Users never notice these, and that is exactly right.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md:\n  Line 193: - Ignore `prefers-reduced-motion` (this is an accessibility violation)\n\n  Line 208: When the motion clarifies state instead of decorating it, hand off to `{{command_prefix}}impeccable polish` for the final pass.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/impeccable.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Use when the user wants to design, redesign, shape, critique, audit, polish, clarify, distill, harden, optimize, adapt, animate, colorize, extract, or otherwise improve a frontend interface. Covers websites, landing pages, dashboards, product UI, app shells, components, forms, settings, onboarding, and empty states. Handles UX review, visual hierarchy, information architecture, cognitive load, accessibility, performance, responsive behavior, theming, anti-patterns, typography, fonts, spacing, layout, alignment, color, motion, micro-interactions, UX copy, error states, edge cases, i18n, and reusable design systems or tokens. Also use for bland designs that need to become bolder or more delightful, loud designs that should become quieter, live browser iteration on UI elements, or ambitious visual effects that should feel technically extraordinary. Not for backend-only or non-UI tasks.\"\n\n  Line 11: Designs and iterates production-grade frontend interfaces. Real working code, committed design choices, exceptional craft.\n\n  Line 18: 2. If the user invoked a sub-command (`craft`, `shape`, `audit`, `polish`, ...), you MUST read `reference/<command>.md` next. Non-optional. The reference defines the command's flow; without it you will skip steps the user expects.\n\n  Line 25: Produce ready-to-ship, production-grade code, not prototypes or starting points. Take no shortcuts unless the user asks for them (when in doubt, ask). Don't stop until arriving at a complete implementation (beautiful, responsive, fast, precise, bug-free, on brand). You take attention to detail seriously: every page, section or component crafted is battle tested using the tools available to you (browser screenshotting, computer use, etc). {{model}} is capable of extraordinary work. Don't hold back.\n\n  Line 128: | `critique [target]` | Evaluate | UX design review with heuristic scoring | [reference/critique.md](reference/critique.md) |\n\n  Line 130: | `polish [target]` | Refine | Final quality pass before shipping | [reference/polish.md](reference/polish.md) |\n\n  Line 134: | `harden [target]` | Refine | Production-ready: errors, i18n, edge cases | [reference/harden.md](reference/harden.md) |\n\n  Line 142: | `clarify [target]` | Fix | Improve UX copy, labels, and error messages | [reference/clarify.md](reference/clarify.md) |\n\n  Line 153:    Reason over the signals; there is no score to obey:\n\n  Line 155:    - `critique.latest` is `null` → the project has never been critiqued; for a set-up project with a real surface, offering `/impeccable critique <surface>` is a strong default.\n\n  Line 156:    - `critique.latest` with a low `score` or non-zero `p0` / `p1` → `polish` (it reads that snapshot as its backlog), or re-run `critique` if the snapshot looks stale.\n\n  Line 157:    - `git.changedFiles` pointing at one surface → scope `audit` or `polish` to those files specifically, naming them.\n\n  Line 161:    **If `scan.targets` is non-empty, run `node {{scripts_path}}/detect.mjs --json <scan.targets joined by spaces>` once** (the bundled detector over local files: no network, no npx). `scan.via` tells you what they are: `git-changes` (the markup/style files in your dirty tree, the most relevant set), `source-dir` (e.g. `src`, `app`), `html`, or `root`. Fold the hits into your picks: many quality / contrast hits → `audit` or `polish`; a specific slop family → the matching command (gradient text or eyebrows → `quieter` / `typeset`, flat or gray palette → `colorize`, and so on). It's a real, current signal that beats guessing. If detect errors or the tree is large and slow, skip it and recommend the user run `audit` themselves; never block the suggestion on it.\n\n  Line 165: 3. **First word doesn't match, but the intent clearly maps to one command** (e.g. \"fix the spacing\" → `layout`, \"rewrite this error message\" → `clarify`, \"the colors feel flat\" → `colorize`): load that command's reference and proceed as if invoked. If two commands could fit, ask once which.\n\n  Line 186: `{{command_prefix}}impeccable hooks <on|off|status|ignore-rule|ignore-file|ignore-value|reset>` manages the design detector hook for this project. The hook auto-runs the detector after direct UI file edits and surfaces findings as system reminders. Full flow is in [reference/hooks.md](reference/hooks.md); load it when the user invokes `{{command_prefix}}impeccable hooks` with any argument.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/optimize.md:\n  Line 15:    - **Core Web Vitals**: LCP, FID/INP, CLS scores\n\n  Line 119: - Use `transform` and `opacity` for reliable movement, but allow blur, filters, masks, clip paths, shadows, and color shifts when they create meaningful polish\n\n  Line 247: - Sacrifice accessibility for performance\n\n  Line 258: - **Before/after metrics**: Compare Lighthouse scores\n\n  Line 265: When the user-facing numbers move, hand off to `{{command_prefix}}impeccable polish` for the final pass.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md:\n  Line 2: name: critique\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Evaluate design quality with structured UX scoring, persona checks, and actionable remediation guidance.\"\n\n  Line 10: Resolve one stable target, run two independent assessments, synthesize a design critique, persist a snapshot, and ask the user what to improve next. The chat response is the primary deliverable; the snapshot is an archive/backlog for future commands.\n\n  Line 15: - Assessment A must finish before detector findings enter the parent synthesis context. Detector output is deterministic, but it still anchors judgment.\n\n  Line 17: - A skipped detector is a failed critique run unless `detect.mjs` is missing or crashes after a real attempt.\n\n  Line 19: - Any local server started only for critique visualization must run in the background, have a recorded stop method, and be stopped before final reporting unless the user asks to keep it.\n\n  Line 30:    node {{scripts_path}}/critique-storage.mjs slug \"<resolved-path-or-url>\"\n\n  Line 32:    Keep it. If the command exits non-zero, skip persistence and trend for this run, but continue the critique.\n\n  Line 33: 3. **Read `.impeccable/critique/ignore.md`** if it exists. Drop matching findings silently; it is the only prior-run input critique consumes.\n\n  Line 37: Delegate Assessment A and Assessment B to separate sub-agents when possible. They must not see each other's output. Do not show findings to the user until synthesis.\n\n  Line 42: - If `spawn_agent` is exposed but the user did not explicitly allow sub-agents, ask exactly once: \"Impeccable critique is designed to run two independent sub-agents for an unanchored assessment. May I use sub-agents for this critique?\" Then stop until the user answers.\n\n  Line 57: - **Holistic design**: hierarchy, IA, emotional fit, discoverability, composition, typography, color, accessibility, states, copy, and edge cases.\n\n  Line 60: - **Nielsen heuristics**: consult the [Heuristics Scoring Guide](#heuristics-scoring-guide) section below; score all 10 heuristics 0-4.\n\n  Line 62: Return: AI slop verdict, heuristic scores, cognitive load, emotional journey, 2-3 strengths, 3-5 priority issues, persona red flags, minor observations, and provocative questions.\n\n  Line 76: - Exit code 0 = clean; 2 = findings.\n\n  Line 91: Return: CLI findings JSON/counts, browser console findings if applicable, false positives, and skipped/failed browser steps with concrete reasons.\n\n  Line 93: After Assessment B returns usable CLI findings, reuse them. Do not rerun `detect.mjs` in the parent unless Assessment B failed, was truncated, or omitted count, rule names, or file locations.\n\n  Line 101: Synthesize both assessments into a single report. Do NOT simply concatenate. Weave the findings together, noting where the LLM review and detector agree, where the detector caught issues the LLM missed, and where detector findings are false positives.\n\n  Line 103: The chat response is the primary user-facing deliverable. Present the full structured critique below in chat; do not replace it with a summary and a link. The persisted snapshot is only an archive/backlog for later commands.\n\n  Line 106: Codex final-answer note: `$impeccable critique` produces a report artifact, so the final chat response should intentionally exceed the usual concise close-out style. Do not title the final response \"Critique Summary\" unless the user explicitly asked for a summary.\n\n  Line 114: Present the Nielsen's 10 heuristics scores as a table:\n\n  Line 130: Be honest with scores. A 4 means genuinely excellent. Most real interfaces score 20-32.\n\n  Line 151: For each issue, tag with **P0-P3 severity** (see [Issue Severity below](#issue-severity-p0p3) for definitions):\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"accessibility|WCAG|critique|polish|harden|pseudo|clarify|findings|severity|score|production|remediation","time":{"start":1782487017258,"end":1782487017295}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f51f328f999505f016a3e97e904dc819199bd07a8a4a5d53b"}},"id":"prt_f04816726001MC8TNbA1yotNLd","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f04808072001FIfGI2zYQRHcqY"}}
