n\n  Line 11:   wants to create slides, infographics, or visual reports with a clean Apple aesthetic.\n\n  Line 24: Creating visually polished presentation graphics typically requires design tools like Figma or Keynote. This skill generates Apple-quality bento grid layouts as self-contained HTML files that screenshot into pixel-perfect images — no design tool needed.\n\n  Line 28: Generate self-contained HTML files that render Apple-inspired bento card grids. Each output is a single HTML file with inline CSS — no dependencies except Google Fonts. Cards fill a tight CSS grid with minimal gaps, ready for Playwright screenshot export at 2x resolution. Both light and dark themes are available.\n\n  Line 49: After generating the HTML, always view the output to catch visual issues before presenting to the user. Use Playwright, browser MCP tools, or `open` to render the file, then check for:\n\n  Line 63: If any issues are found, fix the HTML and re-check. Do not present to the user until the output passes visual review.\n\n  Line 71: | Slide deck / presentation | **Dark** — higher visual impact on projectors |\n\n  Line 105: | A: Horizontal | 4-col | 1200px | 52/25 | 12-16 cards, slides |\n\n  Line 130: Edit the `pages` array in `screenshot.mjs` to point to your HTML files. Each entry needs: `file` (HTML path), `output` (PNG path), `viewportWidth` (match grid width).\n\n  Line 136: **After screenshotting, always view the output image** to verify no edges are clipped. Check that the rightmost and bottommost cards are fully visible with their border-radius intact.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bolder.md:\n  Line 46: Create a strategy to increase impact while maintaining coherence:\n\n  Line 68: - **Dominant color strategy**: Let one bold color own 60% of the design\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/soft-skill.md:\n  Line 10: - **Objective:** You engineer $150k+ agency-level digital experiences, not just websites. Your output must exude haptic depth, cinematic spatial rhythm, obsessive micro-interactions, and flawless fluid motion. \n\n  Line 22: Before writing code, silently \"roll the dice\" and select ONE combination from the following archetypes based on the prompt's context to ensure the output is uniquely tailored but always premium:\n\n  Line 61: - **Staggered Mask Reveal:** The navigation links inside the expanded state do not just appear. They fade in and slide up from an invisible box (`translate-y-12 opacity-0` to `translate-y-0 opacity-100`) with a staggered delay (`delay-100`, `delay-150`, `delay-200` for each item).\n\n  Line 80: 1. **[SILENT THOUGHT]** Roll the Variance Engine (Section 3). Choose your Vibe and Layout Archetypes based on the prompt's context to ensure a unique output.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/design-system.md:\n  Line 3: Complete design tokens, card components, layout templates, and HTML skeleton for generating Apple-inspired bento grid presentations. Supports both light and dark themes.\n\n  Line 42: **Color assignment strategy:**\n\n  Line 130: Best for: 12-16 cards, landscape slides, full project overviews.\n\n  Line 830: Subtle crosshatch overlay. Optional but recommended for presentation-quality output.\n\n  Line 1161: The dark theme inverts the color scheme for high-impact presentations, slide decks, and social media. Cards use subtle gradient backgrounds with radial glow accents for depth.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/frontend-slides.md:\n  Line 2: name: frontend-slides\n\n  Line 3: description: Create stunning, animation-rich HTML presentations from scratch or by converting PowerPoint files. Use when the user wants to build a presentation, convert a PPT/PPTX to web, or create slides for a talk/pitch. Helps non-designers discover their aesthetic through visual exploration rather than abstract choices.\n\n  Line 8: Create zero-dependency, animation-rich HTML presentations that run entirely in the browser.\n\n  Line 14: 3. **Distinctive Design** — No generic \"AI slop.\" Every presentation must feel custom-crafted.\n\n  Line 16: 5. **Fixed 16:9 Stage (NON-NEGOTIABLE)** — Every deck uses a 1920×1080 slide canvas scaled as a whole to the viewport. Slides must stay 16:9 on every screen, including phones. Do not reflow slide content to fit the device.\n\n  Line 20: You tend to converge toward generic, \"on distribution\" outputs. In frontend design, this creates what users call the \"AI slop\" aesthetic. Avoid this: make creative, distinctive frontends that surprise and delight.\n\n  Line 40: These invariants apply to EVERY slide in EVERY presentation:\n\n  Line 43: - Every slide is authored inside a fixed 1920×1080 stage.\n\n  Line 45: - Do not use responsive breakpoints to rearrange slide content for phones.\n\n  Line 46: - Use fixed internal slide measurements at the 1920×1080 design size.\n\n  Line 47: - Slide visibility must be controlled by `.active` / `.visible` using `visibility`, `opacity`, and `pointer-events` from `viewport-base.css`. Do not use `display: none` / `display: block` for slide switching; later layout classes such as `.slide-content { display: flex; }` can override them and make every slide visible at once.\n\n  Line 48: - Use `clamp()` only for non-slide UI outside the stage, or for small fallback previews where a full stage is impractical.\n\n  Line 52: **When generating, read `viewport-base.css` and include its full contents in every presentation.**\n\n  Line 60: | **Low density / speaker-led** | Public talks, keynote-style sharing, live explanation | One idea per slide, large type, strong visual hierarchy, generous negative space, 1-3 bullets max, more slides if needed |\n\n  Line 61: | **High density / reading-first** | Reports, handouts, async review, detailed internal docs | More self-contained slides, structured grids/tables/annotations, 4-8 bullets or 4-6 cards when readable, tighter but still intentional spacing |\n\n  Line 63: Baseline limits still apply: no scrolling, no overflow, no overlapping panels, and no text below comfortable reading size. If content exceeds the selected density mode, split it into more slides instead of shrinking until it becomes cramped.\n\n  Line 73: - **Mode C: Enhancement** — Improve an existing HTML presentation. Read it, understand it, enhance. **Follow Mode C modification rules below.**\n\n  Line 77: When enhancing existing presentations, fixed-stage fitting is the biggest risk:\n\n  Line 80: 2. **Adding images:** Fit them inside the 1920×1080 slide canvas. If slide already has max content, split into two slides\n\n  Line 81: 3. **Adding text:** Max 4-6 bullets per slide. Exceeds limits? Split into continuation slides\n\n  Line 82: 4. **After ANY modification, verify:** the slide stage remains 16:9, no text overflows its card, no panels overlap, and screenshots look correct at 1280×720 plus one phone viewport\n\n  Line 85: **When adding images to existing slides:** Move image to a new slide or reduce other content first. Never add images without checking if existing content already fills the 1920×1080 slide stage.\n\n  Line 94: What is this presentation for? Options: Pitch deck / Teaching-Tutorial / Conference talk / Internal presentation\n\n  Line 97: Approximately how many slides? Options: Short 5-10 / Medium 10-20 / Long 20+\n\n  Line 110: Remember the user's density choice. It affects slide count, typography scale, amount of text per slide, layout density, and whether to favor cinematic presenter slides or self-contained reading slides.\n\n  Line 123: 4. **Co-design the outline** — Curated images inform slide structure alongside text. This is NOT \"plan slides then add images\" — design around both from the start (e.g., 3 screenshots → 3 feature slides, 1 logo → title/closing slide)\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"canvas|slide|presentation|process|research|strategy|output|anti-truncation|UX strategy","time":{"start":1782487017262,"end":1782487017297}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f51f328f999505f016a3e97e904f0819199b7b5a70fe0d90f"}},"id":"prt_f0481672d001iA90FXy8W3ju2j","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f04808072001FIfGI2zYQRHcqY"}}
