{"type":"text","timestamp":1782487378466,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"id":"prt_f0486ab5c001g2kzIaU845QvU1","messageID":"msg_f048690e000125PADqaXN4pdu2","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","type":"text","text":"The lineage currently has only executor/log scaffolding, so I’ll create canonical `deep-research-*` state files, one iteration, one delta, registry, dashboard, resource map, and final synthesis inside it.","time":{"start":1782487362396,"end":1782487378465},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_056f0a4e731df122016a3e99425b8481919fa5d6f6cf565657","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487378558,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_rzwuNm3TA4n93GtBHuucxEic","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"^##|^###|G[0-9]|N[0-9]|brand|Brand|bolder|quieter|distill|transform|AIDA|gapless|copy|motion|audit|accessibility|DESIGN.md|asset","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research","include":"gap-analysis.md"},"output":"Found 27 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:\n  Line 4: > **Question:** Of the external design-skills corpus, what techniques / topics are MISSING or under-covered in the converted `sk-design` family (`design-interface`, `design-foundations`, `design-motion`, `design-audit`, `design-md-generator`), and what should be added?\n\n  Line 6: > **Provenance:** a 2-model fan-out produced a 16-gap baseline (recovered from a completed run's logs after an in-sandbox write-block); that baseline was then **re-validated by a current-state Opus-4.8 pass** against the converted family — it read all 5 packet SKILL.md + `shared/` + the corpus, confirmed 15/16, marked 0 now-covered, revised 5 severities/framings, reclassified 2 as scope rulings, and added 3 new gaps (N1–N3). The full per-gap prose lives in `scratchpad/gap-research/run2/opus.log`.\n\n  Line 8: ## Verdict\n\n  Line 10: Baseline substantially correct: **15 confirmed, 0 now-covered, 5 revised, +3 new (N1–N3).** Two baseline items (13 process-lifecycle, 02 canvas) are **scope rulings**, not content gaps.\n\n  Line 12: ## Validated severity summary\n\n  Line 16: | 05 | Brand-vs-Product **operating** register | impeccable, bolder, quieter | `shared/register.md` (new) | **must-add** ⬆ (was should) |\n\n  Line 17: | 04 | Transform verbs (bolder/quieter/distill) | impeccable, bolder, quieter, distill | audit/interface **mode** (not new child) | should-add |\n\n  Line 18: | 07 | Model-specific defect tells (Codex/Gemini) | impeccable | `shared/anti_slop` or audit | should-add |\n\n  Line 19: | 08e | emil advanced interaction/gesture craft | emil-design-eng | `design-motion` | should-add |\n\n  Line 20: | 09 | gpt-taste (AIDA, 2-line hero, gapless bento) | gpt-tasteskill | interface/foundations/motion | should-add |\n\n  Line 21: | 10 | Forward DESIGN.md/PRODUCT.md authoring | stitch-skill, impeccable | **new `design-spec`** | should-add |\n\n  Line 22: | 11 | Redesign/remediation playbook | redesign-skill, taste §11 | audit `remediate` **mode** | should-add |\n\n  Line 26: | N1 | Realistic mock-content / anti-AI-copy | redesign, gpt-taste, impeccable | audit + interface | **should-add (new)** |\n\n  Line 27: | N2 | Mechanical layout pre-flight gate | taste §14, gpt-taste §8, impeccable, redesign | audit + interface | **should-add (new)** |\n\n  Line 30: | 06 | Advanced rendering / overdrive motion | overdrive, gpt-taste, emil | motion advanced ref | nice-to-have |\n\n  Line 32: | 16 | visual-critique 7-lens | designer-skills visual-critique | audit critique_hardening | nice-to-have |\n\n  Line 35: | N3 | Greenfield brand-seed color | impeccable | foundations (fold-in) | nice-to-have (new) |\n\n  Line 39: ## Key revisions vs baseline\n\n  Line 41: - **05 register ⬆ should→must (highest leverage)** — dependency of 04/07/11/N1/N2. Reframed: it's *not* \"0 hits\" — a **color**-register exists in foundations; the impeccable **operating** register (Brand = design IS the product vs Product = design SERVES the product, gating motion budget / density / anti-slop bar) is the missing switch.\n\n  Line 43: - **08 SPLIT**: emil→motion (strong should-add), taste three-dials→config ref (should-add), bencium→nice. **14 SPLIT**: data-viz should-add, Gestalt/grid nice (already largely covered by `cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md`).\n\n  Line 45: - **NEW**: N1 mock-content/anti-AI-copy discipline · N2 mechanical layout pre-flight gate · N3 greenfield brand-seed color.\n\n  Line 47: ## Recommended sequencing\n\n  Line 49: 1. **must-add first:** 05 register (`shared/register.md`) — it gates 04/07/11/N1/N2.\n\n  Line 51: 3. **should-adds by home:** `design-audit` gains the most (07, 11, 16, N1, N2); `design-motion` gains 08e/06; two candidate **new children** — `design-interaction` (15) + `design-spec` (10); `design-foundations` gains 14d + N3.\n\n  Line 53: ## New-children verdict\n\n  Line 55: Fold where possible; reserve NEW children for genuinely-unowned surfaces. **New:** `design-spec` (10, forward-authoring) + `design-interaction` (15, forms/state/nav). **Fold as modes** (not new children): 04 transforms + 11 remediate into existing audit/interface. `design-slides` (01) only if the scope ruling puts presentation in-family. All new-child names use the `design-` prefix.\n\n  Line 57: ## Gate\n","metadata":{"matches":27,"truncated":false},"title":"^##|^###|G[0-9]|N[0-9]|brand|Brand|bolder|quieter|distill|transform|AIDA|gapless|copy|motion|audit|accessibility|DESIGN.md|asset","time":{"start":1782487378528,"end":1782487378553}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_056f0a4e731df122016a3e9952699c8191b18f3cb5819fa976"}},"id":"prt_f0486ea28001xQi0B3erG0f0D1","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f048690e000125PADqaXN4pdu2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487378558,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_qZEapKZ5e3l7EeYsa1WbJtX1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"^##|^###|interface|foundations|motion|audit|md-generator|DESIGN|corpus|taxonomy|mode","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research","include":"research.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md:\n  Line 3: ## 1. Executive Verdict\n\n  Line 5: Create `sk-design` as a thin umbrella router over a sibling family of six child skills, backed by shared core design references. Do not build a single monolithic hub with all modes nested inside one `SKILL.md`.\n\n  Line 11: | `sk-design-strategy` | Brief framing, design read, UX strategy, audience, IA, goals, constraints | UX strategy corpus |\n\n  Line 12: | `sk-design-interface` | New visual/interface direction, UI craft, variation generation, anti-slop taste | Existing `sk-design-interface` |\n\n  Line 13: | `sk-design-interaction` | Interaction flows, state machines, motion, feedback, delight, onboarding | Animate, delight, interaction corpus |\n\n  Line 14: | `sk-design-system` | Tokens, theming, component specs, DESIGN.md, measured extraction | Existing `sk-design-md-generator` as child or alias |\n\n  Line 15: | `sk-design-quality` | Critique, audit, hardening, polish, accessibility, responsiveness, edge cases | Audit, critique, polish, harden corpus |\n\n  Line 18: ## 2. Method\n\n  Line 20: This lineage ran five converged evidence iterations instead of forcing all 20 possible iterations. The final iteration produced compatibility details but no taxonomy-changing evidence, and all key questions were answered.\n\n  Line 22: ## 3. Optimal Sub-Skill Taxonomy\n\n  Line 24: ### 3.1 `sk-design-strategy`\n\n  Line 28: Boundaries: It does not generate final UI, extract tokens, run browser critique, or implement code. It hands a design brief and decision frame to `sk-design-interface`, `sk-design-interaction`, or `sk-design-system`.\n\n  Line 41: ### 3.2 `sk-design-interface`\n\n  Line 43: Scope: Own visual/interface creation: palette, typography, layout, composition, information hierarchy, visual identity, anti-template critique, UI variants, and real UI self-critique.\n\n  Line 45: Boundaries: It does not own measured extraction, token validation, systematic audit, or developer handoff. It can consume outputs from `sk-design-strategy` and `sk-design-system`.\n\n  Line 49: - Existing `sk-design-interface` already defines the two-pass process: ground subject, brainstorm token system, critique defaults, build, self-critique [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-interface/SKILL.md:53-63].\n\n  Line 50: - `ui-design` groups layout grids, color systems, typography, responsive design, visual hierarchy, spacing, dark mode, data visualization, and Gestalt principles [SOURCE: external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/README.md:1-18].\n\n  Line 57: - Keep the existing name `sk-design-interface` as the canonical child name or as a long-lived alias to `sk-design-craft`.\n\n  Line 58: - Preserve current trigger phrases like \"design\", \"redesign\", \"visual identity\", \"looks templated\", and \"multiple directions\" [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-interface/SKILL.md:24-31].\n\n  Line 61: ### 3.3 `sk-design-interaction`\n\n  Line 63: Scope: Own how the interface behaves over time: state machines, navigation patterns, forms, feedback, loading states, error flows, onboarding, micro-interactions, motion, gesture design, and delight moments.\n\n  Line 65: Boundaries: It does not pick the whole visual identity or produce measured design-system docs. It collaborates with `sk-design-interface` for look and with `sk-design-quality` for verification.\n\n  Line 70: - `animate` frames motion as state feedback, hierarchy clarification, and purposeful UX, not decoration [SOURCE: external/animate.md:6-18].\n\n  Line 75: - Route here when the prompt names \"flow\", \"state\", \"motion\", \"animation\", \"onboarding\", \"feedback\", \"loading\", \"forms\", \"navigation\", \"gesture\", or \"delight\".\n\n  Line 76: - Require reduced-motion, performance, and accessibility checks as part of the child contract, then hand off to `sk-design-quality` when the user asks for audit or polish.\n\n  Line 78: ### 3.4 `sk-design-system`\n\n  Line 80: Scope: Own reusable design-system artifacts: tokens, component specs, theming, icon systems, motion tokens, localization, pattern library entries, documentation templates, governance, and measured DESIGN.md extraction.\n\n  Line 82: Boundaries: It captures and structures reusable systems. It does not invent a fresh visual direction unless paired with `sk-design-interface`, and it does not run broad critique unless paired with `sk-design-quality`.\n\n  Line 86: - `design-systems` covers tokens, components, pattern libraries, naming, accessibility audits, theming, icon systems, documentation, motion systems, governance, and localization [SOURCE: external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/README.md:1-18].\n\n  Line 87: - Existing `sk-design-md-generator` captures live website CSS into DESIGN.md with measured tokens and validation [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-14].\n\n  Line 88: - `sk-design-md-generator` has a non-negotiable cardinal fidelity rule that every hex, pixel, font weight, shadow, radius, and spacing value in DESIGN.md comes from `tokens.json` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-md-generator/SKILL.md:248-255].\n\n  Line 93: - Keep `sk-design-md-generator` as a compatibility alias or child entrypoint for URL-to-DESIGN.md workflows.\n\n  Line 94: - Prefer naming the broader child `sk-design-system` while exposing `sk-design-md-generator` for the exact extract/write/validate pipeline.\n\n  Line 95: - Parent router should choose this child for \"DESIGN.md\", \"tokens\", \"extract design system\", \"theme\", \"component spec\", \"pattern library\", \"design system\", and \"capture website CSS\".\n\n  Line 97: ### 3.5 `sk-design-quality`\n\n  Line 99: Scope: Own evaluation, audit, hardening, and final polish: visual critique, technical audit, WCAG/accessibility, performance, theming, responsive behavior, anti-pattern detection, edge cases, errors, empty/loading states, i18n, and final quality gates.\n\n  Line 101: Boundaries: It reports and fixes/refines quality; it does not own initial creative direction. If direction is missing, route to `sk-design-strategy` or `sk-design-interface` first.\n\n  Line 105: - `audit` runs technical quality checks across accessibility, performance, theming, responsive behavior, and anti-patterns [SOURCE: external/audit.md:6-15].\n\n  Line 113: - Route here for \"audit\", \"critique\", \"review design\", \"polish\", \"harden\", \"accessibility\", \"responsive\", \"performance\", \"edge cases\", \"production-ready\", or \"does this look AI-generated?\".\n\n  Line 116: ### 3.6 `sk-design-delivery`\n\n  Line 131: - Keep Apple bento as a specialized reference or sub-mode under delivery rather than a general interface-design child.\n\n  Line 133: ## 4. Parent Structural Model Evidence\n\n  Line 135: ### Option A: Single hub with nested mode packets\n\n  Line 146: - Tool contracts diverge sharply. `sk-design-md-generator` requires Playwright extraction, deterministic token rendering, and validation [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-md-generator/SKILL.md:256-281], while `sk-design-interface` requires creative two-pass judgment and self-critique [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-interface/SKILL.md:94-115].\n\n  Line 147: - Nested mode packets would make isolated maintenance harder because audit, extraction, variant labs, motion, and delivery artifacts all evolve at different rates.\n\n  Line 149: ### Option B: Umbrella router over sibling family\n\n  Line 156: - Allows existing `sk-design-interface` and `sk-design-md-generator` to migrate without breaking names.\n\n  Line 166: ## 5. Shared Runtime and Coupling Boundary\n\n  Line 172: - Shared accessibility/reduced-motion/responsive minimums.\n\n  Line 187: | Ambiguous new design | `sk-design-strategy` -> `sk-design-interface` |\n\n  Line 188: | Build or restyle page/component | `sk-design-interface` plus `sk-code` handoff |\n\n  Line 190: | Extract website design system | `sk-design-system` via `sk-design-md-generator` alias |\n\n  Line 191: | Review or audit existing UI | `sk-design-quality` |\n\n  Line 194: ## 6. Per-Child Onboarding and Compatibility Plan\n\n  Line 196: ### Parent `sk-design`\n\n  Line 208: - Update design transport instructions so Open Design and Figma design judgment routes through parent `sk-design`, which then selects `sk-design-interface` by default.\n\n  Line 210: ### Existing `sk-design-interface`\n\n  Line 220: - Existing prompts and skills that name `sk-design-interface` continue to work.\n\n  Line 223: ### Existing `sk-design-md-generator`\n\n  Line 227: - Fold into `sk-design-system` as the extraction pipeline, or keep as sibling `sk-design-md-generator` with parent route metadata.\n\n  Line 228: - Do not merge its full pipeline into `sk-design-interface`; its cardinal fidelity and validation rules are distinct.\n\n  Line 233: - Parent `sk-design` routes \"generate DESIGN.md\", \"extract design tokens\", \"capture CSS\", and \"validate DESIGN.md\" to this child path.\n\n  Line 235: ### New Children\n\n  Line 243: ## 7. Eliminated Alternatives\n\n  Line 247: | Flat 41-child taxonomy | Over-fragments and conflicts with smallest useful context routing. | `ui-skills-root` says prefer 1 skill, use 2 only for two angles, use 3 only for broad work [SOURCE: external/ui-skills-root.md:41-49]. | 1 |\n\n  Line 248: | Single monolithic hub | Couples different tool contracts and verification gates. | `sk-design-md-generator` extraction pipeline differs from `sk-design-interface` creative process [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-md-generator/SKILL.md:14]. | 4 |\n\n  Line 249: | Separate child for color/layout/type | These axes are interdependent during visual direction and variants. | `sk-design-interface` already plans color, type, layout, and signature together [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-interface/SKILL.md:101-105]. | 2 |\n\n  Line 250: | Put audit/harden/polish inside craft | Quality flows have distinct evidence and verification contracts. | `audit` is technical measurement, not design critique [SOURCE: external/audit.md:8-10]. | 3 |\n\n  Line 251: | Delete existing names immediately | Breaks current references and user muscle memory. | Existing related-skill references name `sk-design-interface` and `sk-design-md-generator` [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design-md-generator/SKILL.md:398-402]. | 5 |\n\n  Line 253: ## 8. Open Questions\n\n  Line 255: - Whether the final child name should be `sk-design-interface` or `sk-design-craft`. Compatibility favors keeping `sk-design-interface`.\n\n  Line 256: - Whether `sk-design-md-generator` should remain a top-level child name or become an alias under `sk-design-system`. Operational clarity favors keeping the alias visible.\n\n  Line 259: ## 9. References\n\n  Line 261: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design-interface/SKILL.md`\n\n  Line 262: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design-md-generator/SKILL.md`\n\n  Line 278: - `external/audit.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/mimo25pro/research.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Deep-research synthesis (mimo25pro lineage, 8 iterations) over the external design-skills corpus to determine the optimal sub-skill taxonomy, structural model, and onboarding strategy for the sk-design family.\"\n\n  Line 6:   - \"design skill taxonomy\"\n\n  Line 13:   model: xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro\n\n  Line 25: ## 1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY\n\n  Line 27: This research determines how to restructure the existing `sk-design-interface` skill into a parent skill named `sk-design` that contains multiple focused design sub-skills. The analysis is grounded in the external design-skills corpus (41 standalone design-skill docs, the designer-skills-main 9-collection/97-skill model, and apple-bento-grid-main).\n\n  Line 31: 1. **Sub-skill taxonomy**: 6 children — visual, color, motion, layout, a11y, interaction\n\n  Line 32: 2. **Structural model**: Umbrella router over sibling family (not a single hub)\n\n  Line 37: ## 2. SUB-SKILL TAXONOMY (6 Children)\n\n  Line 39: ### 2.1 sk-design-visual — Visual Identity & Aesthetics\n\n  Line 45: - DOES NOT OWN: Specific color values (→ sk-design-color), animation (→ sk-design-motion), layout structure (→ sk-design-layout)\n\n  Line 53: - General improvement: make-interfaces-feel-better.md, bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md, emil-design-eng.md\n\n  Line 55: **Existing Skill**: Evolves from `sk-design-interface` (rename + expand). sk-design-interface already covers palette, typography, layout, anti-default — this is the natural home.\n\n  Line 61: ### 2.2 sk-design-color — Color Systems & Tokens\n\n  Line 63: **Scope**: Strategic color systems, OKLCH color space, palette generation, contrast checking, design token architecture, dark mode theming, tinted neutrals.\n\n  Line 66: - OWNS: Color strategy, palette generation, OKLCH conversion, contrast validation, token naming, dark mode token architecture\n\n  Line 71: - colorize.md (264 lines — strategic color introduction, 60-30-10 rule, OKLCH, tinted neutrals, live-mode variant params with `color-amount`)\n\n  Line 74: **Existing Skill**: NEW. Partial overlap with `sk-design-md-generator` (which extracts tokens) — sk-design-color handles strategy, md-generator handles extraction.\n\n  Line 76: **designer-skills-main Absorption**: ui-design plugin (color-system, dark-mode-design), design-systems plugin (design-token, theming-system), visual-critique plugin (critique-color)\n\n  Line 80: ### 2.3 sk-design-motion — Motion & Animation\n\n  Line 82: **Scope**: Purposeful animation, motion principles, micro-interactions, scroll-driven animation, motion performance, spring physics, GSAP patterns, CSS animations.\n\n  Line 85: - OWNS: Animation implementation, motion timing/easing, scroll-triggered animation, motion performance, reduced-motion handling\n\n  Line 87: - OVERLAPS WITH: sk-design-interaction on micro-interactions (motion owns the animation, interaction owns the behavior)\n\n  Line 91: - 12-principles-of-animation.md (248 lines — Disney's 12 principles adapted for web, timing/easing/physics/staging rules with file:line audit format)\n\n  Line 94: - fixing-motion-performance.md (motion performance debugging)\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"^##|^###|interface|foundations|motion|audit|md-generator|DESIGN|corpus|taxonomy|mode","time":{"start":1782487378535,"end":1782487378557}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_056f0a4e731df122016a3e995269b4819198f6fa1b04147897"}},"id":"prt_f0486ea61001OBDjO3AUUSmOXZ","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f048690e000125PADqaXN4pdu2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487378561,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_IRYQyODmmwANH6qHXqbyMCPV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"^#|^##|Use|reference|asset|assets|references|mode|palette|layout|motion|audit|accessibility|DESIGN|extract|quality|anti|taste|brainstorm|tokens|motion budget","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/cardinal_rules_card.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"One-page checklist of the fidelity rules that keep a DESIGN.md hallucination-proof, for a pre-validate self-check.\"\n\n  Line 14: # Cardinal Rules Card\n\n  Line 20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n  Line 22: ### Purpose\n\n  Line 26: ### Usage\n\n  Line 28: Read top to bottom against the draft Style Reference. The value-bearing sections (Tokens — Colors, Tokens — Spacing & Shapes, Surfaces, Quick Start) are pre-rendered by `formatters-v3.ts` and pasted unchanged — verify you did not edit them. Every prose claim must be checkable with evidence in `tokens.json` or the facts block. Anything that cannot be checked is a claim to remove, not to estimate.\n\n  Line 32: ## 2. THE CHECKLIST\n\n  Line 35: □ Every hex, pixel, font-weight, shadow, and radius traces to a value in tokens.json\n\n  Line 36: □ No value was estimated, rounded, normalized, or invented (no \"100rem\" where tokens say \"100%\")\n\n  Line 40: □ Token column uses --color-<slug>, NEVER the extractor's --_color-primitives internal var\n\n  Line 43: □ Quick Start --page-max-width matches tokens maxContentWidth (no concretized/invented value)\n\n  Line 44: □ L1 + L2 tokens are in the main tables; L3 only in a \"Subject to change\" sub-table; L4 excluded\n\n  Line 45: □ Elevation is FLAT (stated plainly) when 0 shadow tokens - never \"gradient-as-depth\"\n\n  Line 46: □ Imagery section is stamped ABSENT (_No <X> data was extracted._) when no imagery signal\n\n  Line 56: ## 3. STABILITY CLASS QUICK REFERENCE\n\n  Line 67: ## 4. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n  Line 70: - [../references/troubleshooting.md](../references/troubleshooting.md) - what to do when validation fails.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/assets/design_md_prompt_template.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"DESIGN.md Write-Phase Prompt Template\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Copy-paste prompt for the WRITE phase: turns an extracted tokens.json into a fidelity-checked v3 Style Reference.\"\n\n  Line 6:   - \"compose style reference from tokens\"\n\n  Line 14: # DESIGN.md Write-Phase Prompt Template\n\n  Line 16: Copy-paste prompt for Phase 2 (WRITE) that composes a v3 **Style Reference** from an extracted `tokens.json`.\n\n  Line 20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n  Line 22: ### Purpose\n\n  Line 24: The WRITE phase used to be where hallucination risk was highest: an agent reading `tokens.json` could estimate a value. In v3 the value-bearing sections are pre-rendered deterministically, so the agent writes prose only and never emits a value. This template front-loads that division of labour and the v3 section contract so the run stays faithful and reads like a named, confident, restrained design-system handoff.\n\n  Line 26: ### Usage\n\n  Line 28: **Run the builder first (mandatory).** Run `npx ts-node backend/scripts/build-write-prompt.ts <TOKENS_JSON_PATH>`. It pre-renders the deterministic value sections — `## Tokens — Colors`, `## Tokens — Spacing & Shapes`, `## Surfaces`, and `## Quick Start` — directly from the tokens via `backend/scripts/formatters-v3.ts` (a hue+lightness colour-namer and emitters), and emits a FACTS block (type scale, shadow/gradient/dark-mode/focus honesty) for the prose sections. Its output IS the prompt: paste the PRE-RENDERED sections into the doc UNCHANGED — never rewrite a value, a colour name, a token slug, or the Quick Start — and write only the prose sections it asks for.\n\n  Line 30: Then fill the three placeholders (`<DOMAIN>`, `<TOKENS_JSON_PATH>`, `<DESIGN_MD_PATH>`) and hand the prompt below to the writing agent. Load `references/design_md_format.md` (the section spec) and `references/writing_style_guide.md` (voice) alongside it.\n\n  Line 34: ## 2. TEMPLATE\n\n  Line 37: Write a v3 Style Reference for <DOMAIN> from the extracted tokens.\n\n  Line 39: Source of truth: <TOKENS_JSON_PATH>. Output: <DESIGN_MD_PATH>.\n\n  Line 42: working material. Read references/design_md_format.md for the section order and\n\n  Line 43: references/writing_style_guide.md for voice before writing.\n\n  Line 45: VOICE: named, confident, restrained — like a design-system handoff, not an extraction\n\n  Line 58: 4. Colours are NAMED (Obsidian Ink, Voltage) with --color-<slug> tokens — never the\n\n  Line 59:    extractor's --_color-primitives internal var. Components are NAMED by function\n\n  Line 64:    0 shadow tokens — never \"gradient-as-depth\". Imagery is stamped ABSENT\n\n  Line 65:    (`_No <X> data was extracted._`) when there is no imagery signal. Dark-mode prose only\n\n  Line 66:    if the tokens detect a dark palette.\n\n  Line 73:   npx ts-node scripts/validate.ts <DESIGN_MD_PATH> <TOKENS_JSON_PATH>\n\n  Line 75: Quick Start hex traces to a token and --page-max-width matches tokens.maxContentWidth.\n\n  Line 81: ## 3. PLACEHOLDER GUIDE\n\n  Line 87: - The extractor output, e.g. `<--output>/tokens.json`.\n\n  Line 89: **`<DESIGN_MD_PATH>`**:\n\n  Line 90: - Where the document is written, e.g. `<--output>/DESIGN.md`.\n\n  Line 94: ## 4. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n  Line 97: - [../references/extraction_workflow.md](../references/extraction_workflow.md) - the full three-phase workflow.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Extracts a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference DESIGN.md via an embedded extract-write-validate pipeline.\"\n\n  Line 8: <!-- Keywords: design system, design tokens, css extraction, design.md, website design extraction, design reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system generator, css tokens, color extraction, typography extraction, hex extraction, shadow extraction, spacing extraction, design fidelity, anti-hallucination -->\n\n  Line 10: # Design System Extractor (md-generator)\n\n  Line 12: Captures a live website's **real, measured CSS** into a publication-quality `DESIGN.md` — a v3 **Style Reference**: a named, role-driven, ship-ready design-system handoff (named colour tokens, semantic type scale, named components, Surfaces, Elevation, Agent Prompt Guide, Similar Brands, and copy-paste Quick Start CSS + Tailwind) that AI agents build against without hallucinating colors, fonts, spacing, or shadows. Runs a three-phase pipeline (extract, write, validate) through an embedded Playwright crawler that samples five viewports and emits verbatim `tokens.json`. Deep operational detail lives in [`references/`](references/).\n\n  Line 14: > **Family boundary.** This skill is the **extraction and format-fidelity engine** of the `sk-design-*` family. It captures what already exists. Sibling `interface` invents **new** distinctive direction (palette, type, anti-default critique). The transports — `mcp-open-design` and `mcp-figma` — move design data; this skill produces the authoritative reference those transports and `interface` consume.\n\n  Line 18: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\n  Line 20: ### Activation Triggers\n\n  Line 22: **Use when** the user wants to:\n\n  Line 23: - Extract a live website's real CSS into a machine-readable `DESIGN.md` v3 Style Reference, with every hex, pixel, font-weight, radius, and shadow copied verbatim from the running page.\n\n  Line 24: - Produce a hallucination-proof design document for an AI agent to code against — `DESIGN.md` replaces guesses with measured ground truth.\n\n  Line 25: - Capture colors (including dark-mode palette if detected), typography stacks, shadows, border-radii, spacing scales, CSS custom properties, framework markers, icon-system hints, motion tokens, and a11y data across five responsive viewports.\n\n  Line 26: - Validate a generated `DESIGN.md` against its source `tokens.json` to confirm hex accuracy and section completeness.\n\n  Line 27: - Generate visual validation reports (HTML preview, diff report) from a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair.\n\n  Line 28: - Re-extract a site after a redesign to update the design-system reference.\n\n  Line 30: **Keyword Triggers**: \"extract design system\", \"generate DESIGN.md\", \"capture website css\", \"design tokens from url\", \"create design reference\", \"anti-hallucination design doc\", \"design-to-markdown\", \"extract design tokens\".\n\n  Line 32: ### Use Cases\n\n  Line 34: **Full extraction — URL to DESIGN.md.** The canonical workflow: crawl a live URL, produce `tokens.json`, write `DESIGN.md` output conforming to the v3 Style Reference format, then validate hex accuracy, section completeness, and Quick-Start fidelity. This is the primary path.\n\n  Line 36: **Validation-only.** The user already has a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair (from a prior extraction or hand-edited) and wants to confirm fidelity. Run the validator without re-extracting.\n\n  Line 38: **Visual report generation.** Given a `DESIGN.md` + `tokens.json` pair, render an HTML preview and a visual-diff report to confirm the written doc matches the extracted tokens.\n\n  Line 40: **Example study.** The user wants to understand how a gold-standard site (stripe, vercel, linear, supabase — included in `references/examples/`) structures its DESIGN.md output, to inform a new extraction or to learn the format conventions.\n\n  Line 42: ### When NOT to Use\n\n  Line 45: - The task is **inventing a new design direction** (palette, type scale, the anti-default critique). That is `interface`. This skill captures; that skill creates.\n\n  Line 46: - The target is a **Figma file**, not a live website. Use `mcp-figma` to extract from Figma Desktop.\n\n  Line 47: - The target is an **Open Design project**. Use `mcp-open-design`.\n\n  Line 48: - The user only wants a **screenshot or visual preview** of a page. Use `mcp-chrome-devtools`.\n\n  Line 53: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\n  Line 55: ### Primary Detection Signal\n\n  Line 60: # Phase detection (pseudo)\n\n  Line 63: echo \"$REQUEST\" | grep -qiE 'example|gold.*standard|stripe|vercel|linear|supabase|reference.*format' && PHASE=\"STUDY\"\n\n  Line 64: # default for extract/write/url/crawl:\n\n  Line 67: # Tool readiness check\n\n  Line 71: ### Phase Detection\n\n  Line 78:     +- Phase 1: EXTRACT — crawl URL across 5 viewports, emit tokens.json\n\n  Line 84: ### Resource Domains\n\n  Line 86: The router discovers knowledge from a single root domain — this skill's `references/` directory: eight reference docs covering the v3 format spec and writing-style guide, the colour and component taxonomies, anti-patterns, the quality checklist, and the operational extraction-workflow and troubleshooting guides. Examples under `references/examples/` are study artifacts, not resources.\n\n  Line 89: references/design_md_format.md    # v3 Style Reference section specification\n\n  Line 90: references/writing_style_guide.md    # voice, tone, section composition rules\n\n  Line 91: references/color_role_taxonomy.md    # color role naming + classification\n\n  Line 92: references/component_taxonomy.md     # component naming + hierarchy patterns\n\n  Line 93: references/anti_patterns.md          # common DESIGN.md mistakes to avoid\n\n  Line 94: references/quality_checklist.md      # pre-validate self-check\n\n  Line 95: references/extraction_workflow.md    # three-phase workflow, invocations, handoff\n\n  Line 96: references/troubleshooting.md        # failure modes and fixes\n\n  Line 97: references/examples/{stripe,vercel,linear,supabase}/  # gold-standard DESIGN.md + tokens.json pairs\n\n  Line 100: ### Resource Loading Levels\n\n  Line 104: | ALWAYS      | Every invocation                     | `references/design_md_format.md`, `references/writing_style_guide.md`, `assets/cardinal_rules_card.md` (pre-write fabrication gate) |\n\n  Line 105: | CONDITIONAL | EXTRACT_WRITE intent                 | `references/color_role_taxonomy.md`, `references/component_taxonomy.md`, `references/anti_patterns.md` |\n\n  Line 106: | CONDITIONAL | VALIDATE / completion claim          | `references/quality_checklist.md`, `references/anti_patterns.md`  |\n\n  Line 107: | CONDITIONAL | STUDY intent                         | `references/examples/` (one site at a time, loaded as reference pairs)           |\n\n  Line 108: | ON_DEMAND   | Deep format edge-cases or component patterns | `references/anti_patterns.md`, `references/component_taxonomy.md` |\n\n  Line 110: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n\n  Line 112: > Resilience pattern: see [sk-doc smart-router template](../sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_smart_router.md). Guard paths, discover at runtime, score intents, fall back to the full extract-write-validate pipeline when unsure.\n\n  Line 118: RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\",)\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"^#|^##|Use|reference|asset|assets|references|mode|palette|layout|motion|audit|accessibility|DESIGN|extract|quality|anti|taste|brainstorm|tokens|motion budget","time":{"start":1782487378540,"end":1782487378560}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_056f0a4e731df122016a3e995269c4819185617aa5b422d400"}},"id":"prt_f0486ea6b001QW1Ku2jxym4X94","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f048690e000125PADqaXN4pdu2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487378563,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_scWoBYxS6R62W4zyXcjcCeXB","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"^#|^##|brand|Brand|product|Product|register|transform|bolder|quieter|distill|AIDA|gapless|mock|copy|motion|audit|accessibility|token|font|layout|palette|DESIGN|extract|asset","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Semantic Design System Skill for Google Stitch. Generates agent-friendly DESIGN.md files that enforce premium, anti-generic UI standards — strict typography, calibrated color, asymmetric layouts, perpetual micro-motion, and hardware-accelerated performance.\n\n  Line 6: # Stitch Design Taste — Semantic Design System Skill\n\n  Line 8: ## Overview\n\n  Line 9: This skill generates `DESIGN.md` files optimized for Google Stitch screen generation. It translates the battle-tested anti-slop frontend engineering directives into Stitch's native semantic design language — descriptive, natural-language rules paired with precise values that Stitch's AI agent can interpret to produce premium, non-generic interfaces.\n\n  Line 11: The generated `DESIGN.md` serves as the **single source of truth** for prompting Stitch to generate new screens that align with a curated, high-agency design language. Stitch interprets design through **\"Visual Descriptions\"** supported by specific color values, typography specs, and component behaviors.\n\n  Line 13: ## Prerequisites\n\n  Line 17: ## The Goal\n\n  Line 18: Generate a `DESIGN.md` file that encodes:\n\n  Line 21: 3. **Typographic architecture** — font stacks, scale hierarchy, and anti-patterns\n\n  Line 27: ## Analysis & Synthesis Instructions\n\n  Line 29: ### 1. Define the Atmosphere\n\n  Line 37: ### 2. Map the Color Palette\n\n  Line 44: - Stick to one palette for the entire output — no warm/cool gray fluctuation\n\n  Line 47: ### 3. Establish Typography Rules\n\n  Line 51: - **Serif Ban:** Generic serif fonts (`Times New Roman`, `Georgia`, `Garamond`, `Palatino`) are BANNED. If serif is needed for editorial/creative contexts, use only distinctive modern serifs: `Fraunces`, `Gambarino`, `Editorial New`, or `Instrument Serif`. Serif is always BANNED in dashboards or software UIs\n\n  Line 55: ### 4. Define the Hero Section\n\n  Line 60: - **Asymmetric Structure:** Centered Hero layouts BANNED when variance exceeds 4\n\n  Line 63: ### 5. Describe Component Stylings\n\n  Line 66: - **Cards:** Use ONLY when elevation communicates hierarchy. Tint shadows to background hue. For high-density layouts, replace cards with border-top dividers or negative space\n\n  Line 68: - **Loading States:** Skeletal loaders matching layout dimensions — no generic circular spinners\n\n  Line 72: ### 6. Define Layout Principles\n\n  Line 77: - Contain layouts using max-width constraints (e.g., 1400px centered)\n\n  Line 80: ### 7. Define Responsive Rules\n\n  Line 82: - **Mobile-First Collapse (< 768px):** All multi-column layouts collapse to single column. No exceptions\n\n  Line 90: ### 8. Encode Motion Philosophy\n\n  Line 94: - **Performance:** Animate exclusively via `transform` and `opacity`. Never animate `top`, `left`, `width`, `height`. Grain/noise filters on fixed pseudo-elements only\n\n  Line 96: ### 9. List Anti-Patterns (AI Tells)\n\n  Line 97: Encode these as explicit \"NEVER DO\" rules in the DESIGN.md:\n\n  Line 99: - No `Inter` font\n\n  Line 100: - No generic serif fonts (`Times New Roman`, `Georgia`, `Garamond`) — distinctive modern serifs only if needed\n\n  Line 107: - No 3-column equal card layouts\n\n  Line 110: - No AI copywriting clichés (\"Elevate\", \"Seamless\", \"Unleash\", \"Next-Gen\")\n\n  Line 115: ## Output Format (DESIGN.md Structure)\n\n  Line 118: # Design System: [Project Title]\n\n  Line 120: ## 1. Visual Theme & Atmosphere\n\n  Line 121: (Evocative description of the mood, density, variance, and motion intensity.\n\n  Line 122: Example: \"A restrained, gallery-airy interface with confident asymmetric layouts\n\n  Line 123: and fluid spring-physics motion. The atmosphere is clinical yet warm — like a\n\n  Line 126: ## 2. Color Palette & Roles\n\n  Line 135: ## 3. Typography Rules\n\n  Line 139: - **Banned:** Inter, generic system fonts for premium contexts. Serif fonts banned in dashboards.\n\n  Line 141: ## 4. Component Stylings\n\n  Line 145: * **Loaders:** Skeletal shimmer matching exact layout dimensions. No circular spinners.\n\n  Line 148: ## 5. Layout Principles\n\n  Line 153: ## 6. Motion & Interaction\n\n  Line 156: transforms only. Isolated Client Components for CPU-heavy animations.)\n\n  Line 158: ## 7. Anti-Patterns (Banned)\n\n  Line 160: no neon glows, no 3-column equal grids, no AI copywriting clichés,\n\n  Line 164: ## Best Practices\n\n  Line 171: ## Tips for Success\n\n  Line 172: 1. Start with the atmosphere — understand the vibe before detailing tokens\n\n  Line 178: ## Common Pitfalls to Avoid\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/optimize.md:\n  Line 6: # Optimize\n\n  Line 10: ## Assess Performance Issues\n\n  Line 29: ## Optimization Strategy\n\n  Line 33: ### Loading Performance\n\n  Line 72: - Use `font-display: swap` or `optional`\n\n  Line 73: - Subset fonts (only characters you need)\n\n  Line 74: - Preload critical fonts\n\n  Line 75: - Use system fonts when appropriate\n\n  Line 76: - Limit font weights loaded\n\n  Line 79: @font-face {\n\n  Line 80:   font-family: 'CustomFont';\n\n  Line 81:   src: url('/fonts/custom.woff2') format('woff2');\n\n  Line 82:   font-display: swap; /* Show fallback immediately */\n\n  Line 89: - Preload critical assets\n\n  Line 94: ### Rendering Performance\n\n  Line 100:   const height = el.offsetHeight; // Read (forces layout)\n\n  Line 119: - Use `transform` and `opacity` for reliable movement, but allow blur, filters, masks, clip paths, shadows, and color shifts when they create meaningful polish\n\n  Line 120: - Avoid casual animation of layout-driving properties (`width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, margins)\n\n  Line 124: ### Animation Performance\n\n  Line 130:   transform: translateX(100px);\n\n  Line 160: ### React/Framework Optimization\n\n  Line 176: ### Network Optimization\n\n  Line 181: - Inline small critical assets\n\n  Line 189: - CDN for static assets\n\n  Line 197: ## Core Web Vitals Optimization\n\n  Line 199: ### Largest Contentful Paint (LCP < 2.5s)\n\n  Line 206: ### First Input Delay (FID < 100ms) / INP (< 200ms)\n\n  Line 212: ### Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS < 0.1)\n\n  Line 217: - Avoid animations that cause layout shifts\n\n  Line 226: ## Performance Monitoring\n\n  Line 247: - Sacrifice accessibility for performance\n\n  Line 254: ## Verify Improvements\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/ui-skills-root.md:\n  Line 10: # UI Skills Root\n\n  Line 22: ## Protocol\n\n  Line 32: ## CLI\n\n  Line 41: ## Selection Rules\n\n  Line 57: For quick cleanup, prefer the most specific craft, visual, or layout skill available.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/quieter.md:\n  Line 2: name: quieter\n\n  Line 6: # Quieter\n\n  Line 12: ## Register\n\n  Line 14: Brand: \"quieter\" means more restrained palette, more whitespace, more typographic air. Drama is reduced, not eliminated; the POV stays intact.\n\n  Line 16: Product: \"quieter\" means reducing visual noise. Fewer background accents, flatter cards, less color, less motion. The tool should disappear more completely into the task.\n\n  Line 20: ## Assess Current State\n\n  Line 28:    - **Animation excess**: Too much motion or overly dramatic effects\n\n  Line 42: ## Plan Refinement\n\n  Line 53: ## Refine the Design\n\n  Line 57: ### Color Refinement\n\n  Line 59: - **Soften palette**: Replace bright colors with muted tones\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"^#|^##|brand|Brand|product|Product|register|transform|bolder|quieter|distill|AIDA|gapless|mock|copy|motion|audit|accessibility|token|font|layout|palette|DESIGN|extract|asset","time":{"start":1782487378538,"end":1782487378562}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_056f0a4e731df122016a3e995269bc81918aaacfd522ef7bac"}},"id":"prt_f0486ea68001gjTRopQr074EPk","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f048690e000125PADqaXN4pdu2"}}
