{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782487517028,"sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_ulUVMDetwOJUqkPBJGukiXmP","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"visual-critique|critique|7|lens|heuristic|score|persona","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/prototyping-testing/README.md:\n  Line 2: Plan and execute design validation through prototyping strategies, usability testing, heuristic evaluation, and A/B experiments.\n\n  Line 6: - **heuristic-evaluation** — Conduct expert heuristic evaluations using Nielsen's heuristics and domain-specific criteria.\n\n  Line 14: - `/evaluate` — Run a heuristic evaluation of an existing design.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/README.md:\n  Line 51: | Design practice (this repo) | 9 | Research, systems, UX strategy, UI, interaction, prototyping & testing, design ops, the designer's toolkit, visual critique. |\n\n  Line 55: | [Inclusive design](https://github.com/Owl-Listener/inclusive-design-skills) | 6 | Accessible by default: cognitive accessibility, inclusive interaction, accessible content, inclusive personas, adaptive interfaces, accessibility decisions. |\n\n  Line 63: Agentic skills, commands, and plugins for design, from research to systems, UI, interaction, and delivery. **97 skills and 30 commands across 9 plugins.**\n\n  Line 69: | design-research | 12 | 4 | User research: personas, empathy maps, journey maps, interviews, usability testing, card sorting, surveys, and research repositories. |\n\n  Line 74: | prototyping-testing | 8 | 4 | Validate designs: prototyping strategies, usability testing, heuristic evaluation, and A/B experiments. |\n\n  Line 75: | design-ops | 9 | 3 | Streamline operations: critique frameworks, handoff specs, sprint planning, team workflows, design debt, and impact reporting. |\n\n  Line 76: | designer-toolkit | 7 | 3 | Essential utilities: design rationale, presentations, case studies, UX writing, system adoption, and design negotiation. |\n\n  Line 77: | visual-critique | 7 | 2 | Visual critique: hierarchy, brand consistency, composition, typography, colour, affordance, and information density. |\n\n  Line 101: | `/prototyping-testing:evaluate` | prototyping-testing | Run a heuristic evaluation. |\n\n  Line 110: | `/visual-critique:critique-screen` | visual-critique | Run all seven visual critiques on a screen and output a prioritised fix list. |\n\n  Line 111: | `/visual-critique:critique-ux` | visual-critique | Focused functional critique: hierarchy, affordance, and information density. |\n\n  Line 115: **Skills** are domain knowledge units — nouns. They teach Claude about a design topic: how to create a user persona, how to define design tokens, how to write a non-leading interview question.\n\n  Line 117: **Commands** are workflows — verbs. They chain skills together to do a complete job: `/design-research:discover` runs personas, empathy map, and journey map in one go.\n\n  Line 131: Tell Claude: what you're building, who you think the users are, and what problem you're solving. It will run a full discovery cycle — personas, empathy map, journey map — and surface the gaps in your assumptions.\n\n  Line 144: Start with a critique, not new work.\n\n  Line 147: /visual-critique:critique-screen\n\n  Line 154: - `/prototyping-testing:evaluate` — run a heuristic evaluation if you want a fuller audit\n\n  Line 158: **Minimum install for this path:** visual-critique, prototyping-testing, design-ops\n\n  Line 166: | User personas | design-research | — |\n\n  Line 181: This collection covers conventional design. For designing AI products specifically — model interaction, alignment reasoning, error personality, agent orchestration — use the companion collection:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/prototyping-testing/skills/wireframe-spec/SKILL.md:\n  Line 19: - Dynamic content indicators (personalized, data-driven)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/navigation-patterns/SKILL.md:\n  Line 14: - **Top navigation bar** (desktop/web): horizontal links in header; works for 4–7 destinations\n\n  Line 59: - Too many top-level destinations (more than 7 creates choice paralysis; revisit IA before adding nav items)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-ops/skills/design-sprint-plan/SKILL.md:\n  Line 18: - Silent critique and heat map voting\n\n  Line 42: - Team assembled (5-7 people, cross-functional)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/business-design/SKILL.md:\n  Line 34: Competitive analysis from a design lens asks different questions than a feature comparison matrix.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/millers-law/SKILL.md:\n  Line 10: George Miller's 1956 paper proposed that working memory can hold **7 ± 2 items** (5–9). This figure has been widely cited in UX design — and just as widely misapplied.\n\n  Line 11: More recent research (particularly Nelson Cowan, 2001) suggests the realistic limit for **meaningful chunks in working memory is closer to 4 ± 1**. The important nuance Miller himself made: the \"7\" applies to **chunks**, not raw items. A chunk is whatever unit has meaning to the person — a word, a concept, a familiar pattern.\n\n  Line 15: - Don't cite \"7 items\" as a design rule; cite chunking as the strategy\n\n  Line 19: - **Phone numbers and codes**: formatted as chunks (e.g. `555-867-5309`, `XXXX-XXXX` verification codes) for easier recall\n\n  Line 24: - Using \"7 is the limit\" to justify navigation menus of exactly 7 items\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/naming-convention/SKILL.md:\n  Line 26: - Review names in team critiques\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/animation-principles/SKILL.md:\n  Line 19: - Long (400-700ms): complex choreography\n\n  Line 35: - Limit total sequence duration to under 700ms\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/prototyping-testing/skills/heuristic-evaluation/SKILL.md:\n  Line 2: name: heuristic-evaluation\n\n  Line 3: description: Conduct expert heuristic evaluations using Nielsen's heuristics and domain-specific criteria.\n\n  Line 6: You are an expert in conducting systematic heuristic evaluations of digital interfaces.\n\n  Line 8: You evaluate interfaces against established usability heuristics to identify problems before user testing.\n\n  Line 16: 7. **Flexibility and efficiency** — Shortcuts for experts\n\n  Line 27: 7. Compile and prioritize findings\n\n  Line 29: For each issue: heuristic violated, description, location, severity (0-4), screenshot/reference, recommendation.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-ops/skills/design-critique/SKILL.md:\n  Line 2: name: design-critique\n\n  Line 3: description: Facilitate structured design critiques with clear feedback frameworks and actionable outcomes.\n\n  Line 6: You are an expert in facilitating productive design critiques that improve work and grow teams.\n\n  Line 8: You structure and facilitate design critiques that produce clear, actionable feedback.\n\n  Line 36: - Focusing on personal preference instead of user needs\n\n  Line 40: - Separate exploration critiques from refinement critiques\n\n  Line 44: - Make critique a regular ritual, not an event\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/content-strategy/SKILL.md:\n  Line 20: - **Voice**: the consistent personality of the product's writing (helpful, direct, expert, warm…)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/prototyping-testing/skills/user-flow-diagram/SKILL.md:\n  Line 28: 7. Note system actions happening in background\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-ops/skills/design-impact-reporting/SKILL.md:\n  Line 20: - System Usability Scale (SUS) or similar satisfaction scores\n\n  Line 29: - Accessibility compliance score\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/service-blueprint/SKILL.md:\n  Line 40: 7. **Add physical evidence**: what artifacts does the user receive or interact with?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-ops/skills/team-workflow/SKILL.md:\n  Line 17: - **Design critique** (weekly): Structured feedback sessions\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/commands/design-interaction.md:\n  Line 14: 7. **Loading** — Design loading states using `loading-states` skill.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/component-spec/SKILL.md:\n  Line 16: 7. **Accessibility** — ARIA roles, keyboard nav, screen reader, focus management\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/onboarding-design/SKILL.md:\n  Line 51: - **Day-7 / Day-30 retention**: the downstream signal that onboarding quality predicts\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/interfaces-that-feel/SKILL.md:\n  Line 3: description: Apply an emotional resonance lens to any UI. Use when a design is technically correct but flat — to identify what's missing and prescribe specific changes at the copy, motion, and interaction layer.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems