rch to systems, UI, interaction, and delivery. **97 skills and 30 commands across 9 plugins.**\n\n  Line 73: | interaction-design | 16 | 3 | Design meaningful interactions: micro-animations, state machines, gestures, feedback, cognitive laws, forms, onboarding, navigation, and search. |\n\n  Line 97: | `/interaction-design:design-interaction` | interaction-design | Design a complete interaction flow. |\n\n  Line 98: | `/interaction-design:map-states` | interaction-design | Model states and transitions for a component. |\n\n  Line 99: | `/interaction-design:error-flow` | interaction-design | Design error handling for a feature. |\n\n  Line 137: - `/interaction-design:design-interaction` — for any flows that have meaningful state or motion\n\n  Line 140: **Minimum install for this path:** design-research, ux-strategy, ui-design, interaction-design\n\n  Line 181: This collection covers conventional design. For designing AI products specifically — model interaction, alignment reasoning, error personality, agent orchestration — use the companion collection:\n\n  Line 206: **design-research → ux-strategy → ui-design / interaction-design → design-systems → design-ops**\n\n  Line 208: Research informs strategy. Strategy shapes UI decisions. Patterns in UI become system components. Systems flow into ops. Working against this grain is fine — but if something feels hard, it's often because a step earlier in the sequence was skipped.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/README.md:\n  Line 12: - **information-architecture** — Design the structure, hierarchy, and navigation model for a product's content and features.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/CHANGELOG.md:\n  Line 9: First stable release. Tagging the current state of main as v1.0.0 to give integrators a stable version to pin to.\n\n  Line 14: - Plugins: design-research, design-systems, ux-strategy, ui-design, interaction-design, prototyping-testing, design-ops, designer-toolkit, visual-critique\n\n  Line 22: - **critique-affordance** — clickability signals, state visibility, CTA clarity, and action discoverability\n\n  Line 44: | 2026-04 | Add 9 UX design principle skills across ui-design and interaction-design |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/prototyping-testing/README.md:\n  Line 10: - **click-test-plan** — Design click/first-click tests to evaluate navigation and information findability.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/prototyping-testing/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 66: - Run on every page/state\n\n  Line 69: - Keyboard-only navigation\n\n  Line 101: description: Design click/first-click tests to evaluate navigation and information findability.\n\n  Line 104: You are an expert in designing click tests that evaluate findability and navigation clarity.\n\n  Line 114: What navigation or findability question are you answering?\n\n  Line 116: Screen designs or prototypes to test. Identify which pages/states to show.\n\n  Line 196: Digital wireframes, clickable prototypes, gray-box layouts. Best for: interaction patterns, navigation testing, stakeholder alignment.\n\n  Line 198: Pixel-perfect mockups, coded prototypes, motion prototypes. Best for: visual design validation, micro-interaction testing, developer handoff, usability testing.\n\n  Line 202: - **Interactive prototypes**: Stateful with real interactions\n\n  Line 241: What to watch for: hesitations, facial expressions, verbal comments, navigation choices, error recovery behavior.\n\n  Line 316: - Headers and navigation\n\n  Line 320: - Footers and secondary navigation\n\n  Line 342: - Real labels for navigation and buttons\n\n  Line 347: - Show multiple states (empty, loading, populated, error)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/information-architecture/SKILL.md:\n  Line 3: description: Design the structure, hierarchy, and navigation model for a product's content and features.\n\n  Line 12: - Shows parent/child relationships and navigation depth\n\n  Line 13: - Distinguishes primary navigation from utility navigation\n\n  Line 16: - **Global navigation**: present everywhere (header nav, bottom tab bar)\n\n  Line 17: - **Local navigation**: contextual to the current section (sidebar, tabs, breadcrumbs)\n\n  Line 18: - **Utility navigation**: account, settings, help — high reach, low frequency\n\n  Line 22: - Consistent labeling across navigation, headings, search, and empty states\n\n  Line 32: - **Scent**: do navigation labels and category names accurately predict what's inside?\n\n  Line 38: 4. **Validate**: tree test the draft IA with target users before building navigation components\n\n  Line 42: - Conflating navigation structure with URL structure\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/design-systems/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 20: - **Operable**: Keyboard access, time limits, no seizures, navigation, input modalities\n\n  Line 34: - Check static and interactive states\n\n  Line 41: description: Write a detailed component specification including props, states, variants, accessibility requirements, and usage guidelines.\n\n  Line 46: You create complete component specs covering anatomy, behavior, variants, states, accessibility, and usage.\n\n  Line 58: - Include examples for every variant and state\n\n  Line 102: 3. **Design**: component designed and specced (states, variants, accessibility, tokens)\n\n  Line 131: - Documented props, variants, and states\n\n  Line 132: - Accessibility review (WCAG AA minimum, keyboard navigation, screen reader tested)\n\n  Line 166: Pattern: {category}-{property}-{variant}-{state}\n\n  Line 186: Title, status, when to use, example, anatomy, variants, props, states, accessibility, content guidelines, tokens, related, changelog.\n\n  Line 188: Problem statement, context, solution, behavior, examples (good/bad), accessibility, related patterns.\n\n  Line 220: Categories: action, navigation, content, communication, social, status, file, device\n\n  Line 262: - **Layout mirroring**: sidebars, navigation, and content areas flip; left margin becomes right margin\n\n  Line 289: - Hand gestures (thumbs up, OK sign) have offensive meanings in some cultures — avoid\n\n  Line 290: - Postal and civic icons (mailbox, house, phone) vary by region — use abstract or universally-recognizable forms\n\n  Line 327: | `duration-normal` | 200ms | Default for most transitions (dropdown open, focus ring) |\n\n  Line 336: | `ease-standard` | cubic-bezier(0.2, 0, 0, 1) | Most UI transitions — elements moving between states |\n\n  Line 339: | `ease-spring` | spring / cubic-bezier(0.34, 1.56, 0.64, 1) | Playful or tactile interactions (FAB expand, drawer bounce) |\n\n  Line 350: - **Replace**: substitute instant state changes or simple opacity fades (opacity transitions are generally acceptable)\n\n  Line 351: - **Preserve**: keep animations that convey essential state information (loading spinners, progress)\n\n  Line 360: - Example: \"Purposeful — every animation communicates a state change or relationship\"\n\n  Line 383: - **Components**: [category]/[name]/[variant]/[state]\n\n  Line 384: - **Tokens**: {category}-{property}-{concept}-{variant}-{state}\n\n  Line 411: - **Solution** — The pattern, key principles, visual/interaction description\n\n  Line 414: - **Behavior** — User flow, state changes, error handling\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/commands/frame-problem.md:\n  Line 10: 3. **Define** — Write clear problem statement using `design-brief` skill.\n\n  Line 16: Problem definition with statement, scope, constraints, success criteria, principles, and prioritized sub-problems.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/north-star-vision/SKILL.md:\n  Line 8: You help teams define a north-star vision — a compelling future state that inspires alignment and guides trade-offs.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/experience-map/SKILL.md:\n  Line 8: You create experience maps showing the entire ecosystem of user interactions across touchpoints, channels, and time.\n\n  Line 24: - Map current state before future state\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/service-blueprint/SKILL.md:\n  Line 16: **Line of interaction**: separates user actions from frontstage\n\n  Line 18: **Line of internal interaction**: separates backstage from support processes\n\n  Line 49: - Blueprint existing state first, future state second — don't skip the as-is\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/content-strategy/SKILL.md:\n  Line 21: - **Tone**: how voice adjusts to context (reassuring in error states, celebratory in success states, neutral in legal content)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/design-token/SKILL.md:\n  Line 21: Pattern: {category}-{property}-{variant}-{state}\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/component-spec/SKILL.md:\n  Line 3: description: Write a detailed component specification including props, states, variants, accessibility requirements, and usage guidelines.\n\n  Line 8: You create complete component specs covering anatomy, behavior, variants, states, accessibility, and usage.\n\n  Line 20: - Include examples for every variant and state\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/icon-system/SKILL.md:\n  Line 15: Categories: action, navigation, content, communication, social, status, file, device\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/design-system-governance/SKILL.md:\n  Line 38: 3. **Design**: component designed and specced (states, variants, accessibility, tokens)\n\n  Line 67: - Documented props, variants, and states\n\n  Line 68: - Accessibility review (WCAG AA minimum, keyboard navigation, screen reader tested)\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"forms|state|navigation|interaction|gesture|dialog|combobox|tabs|dropdown","time":{"start":1782487517009,"end":1782487517029}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0cc579814642de46016a3e99dca02c8191aa08f103bdb77297"}},"id":"prt_f048906e200175H79s0EUqX86M","sessionID":"ses_0fb835c90ffeqUAmvkS8gfEWSy","messageID":"msg_f0488bafe001arzRVbGqsdFTyD"}}
